    'body' => '>
>> IMTU, that vector is rtained in relation to the two most gravitationally
>> significant bodies, in the manner of vector angle to ray S1->S2 at jump
>> out, and the vector at jump in will be the same in relation to ray
>> S1\'->S2\'. Note that S1 is the most significant gravity well, and S2 is the
>> second most significant. Generally, this will be the star and planet, or
>> planet and moon. IMTU, ships leaving Terra/Sol tend to choose where to jump
>> based upon lunal vs solar significance, and how it will affect their vector
>> at jump-in. Also, case in point problem If you jump from earth (S1= Earth,
>> S2=Luna) to mars orbit, S1 becomes mars, and S2 is Sol. However, if you
>> instead jump to mercury, S1 is sol, and S2 is Mercury. If however, you jump
>> from nearer Luna than earth,  you might get a reciprical course from what
>> you expect. also note that I use the orbital plane of the S1-S2 pair to
>> determine 3d referents; if you appear to hold S1 still, and S2 moves
>> clockwise around it, you\'re looking "Down". (Even if S2 is the orbital
>> center, as in a two body calculation either one may be the "Stable point"
>> for viewing.)
>
>Slight problem. There are *two* possible vectors that satisfy your
>conditions in some cases. Consider two bodies of equal mass orbiting
>about their common center of mass. And even in the cases where the
>masses differ, something about your using the "orbital direction" to
>define "up & down" bothers me.

By using the motion of a S2 in relationship to S1, you define a plane (s2
\'s apparent orbital motion circumscribes a plane; for reference I use
down/"below the plane" to mean that looking toward the plane at s1, s2 will
appear to move counter clockwise.  This reduces the solution from infinite
vectors to 1 vector.

note also that if, from the direction you\'re looking at the pair from:
If A orbits B clockwise, and you are in the regime of B, a appears to move;
if you are in the regime of A, however, B appears to move clockwise around
A.

also note: I used rays, not lines. A ray has an origin point, but no end
point; the second point establishes a diretion. By applying a vector ray
perpendicular to the ray, at the end of the co-named segment, you define a
three dimensional reference; it is possible to define a bearing and azimuth
accurately now; thus a three dimensional course.

As for doing the math, I\'ve done the math, and we\'ve had this argument
before. 4 years ago. I\'ve not changed my mind, and I don\'t care to. It
means I don\'t have to worry about relative speeds. It meets the letter of
the rules in TNE, and allows for quick calculations, and enables the "Bingo
Jump" phenomena from TNE. (I may hate the rules and the setting, but TNE is
chock full of neat ideas. Often hidden.) Jump Space alone violates
conservation in some ways, by allowing a ship to move to different
potential energy states. IMTU, the universe compensates for the changes in
other ways.

Also, in no case will someone be exactly at the halfway point and not have
a vector and  yet still have to worry about relative vector at exit. If
they are at the halfway point, I generally throw the S1 to the one they are
moving towards. I use acceleration due to gravity to determine signifcance.
I realize the sun is often (but not always) more significant than luna;
luna is however, big enough that it\'s effects (and 100 D limit) make using
it far more interesting than, say, phobos and deimos. It makes for choice
of outgo vector especially critical, and often dependant upon target
system. It creates a readily measureable resting point. In most cases (but
not all) it means the world itself will be the S1.

William F. Hostman  |  "Smith & Wesson: THe original Point and Click
interface!"
