>is free to alter or interpret rules any way he chooses. If that
doesn\'t
>work, he or she will be shown the door.

	I try to forestall that with the following section from my "Player\'s
Introduction" document (plagiarized from many places ... wait, if
it\'s many places it\'s "research" ...)

My basic philosophy for this game is to set the stage ("You\'re next
to a swamp") and the goal ("You need a bridge across the swamp"). You
decide who goes into the swamp to build the bridge, and I just make
sure the alligators in the swamp get equal air time. In order to have
a common framework, and throw in an element of "realism" and
fairness, I\'ll use the mechanics of GDW\'s rules, with my own
modifications. My goal is to be fair and consistent and while I
welcome your observations and help, I am the final arbitrator of the
rules. If, during the game, you have a question or complaint about my
interpretation of the rules, I\'ll try to answer it briefly, but I\'d
rather make a slight consistent error and continue with the plot for
everyone to enjoy rather than spends hours arguing. I may ask you to
wait until after the session to keep things from bogging down. If you
disagree about the rules themselves, please save it for between
sessions. We all want to keep the action flowing.

