    'date' => 'Mon, 13 Dec 1999 09:57:15 +1300',
    'body' => 'On 11 Dec 99, at 10:42, Jim & Peta Lawrie wrote:
 
>     With the rise of reliable battlefield communications there is less and
> less squad autonomy. Commanders can sit in orbit and watch close to real
> time events unfold on their myriad displays and issue orders as needed
> (I\'m assuming orbital superiority but similiar systems can be emplaced.)
> Also, it costs a lot to send a unit out with its advanced equipment and
> warbot grunts and the lethality of the individual soldier has gone through
> the roof. One trooper may well have the firepower of an earlier tech
> levels squad so less troops may in fact be sent. This gives the CO less
> troops to oversee and intensifies his control. These are just a few
> factors among many but I thought I\'d mention them.

OTOH with battlefield support weapon\'s effectiveness and reach 
continuing to improve, along with ELINT probably improving pretty much 
in step with communications the actual seperation of each nam from his 
fellows will probably contiue to increase. This means that while the CO 
may have better contact with his troops they will be spread over more 
and more territory, so in actual fact he could well have less and less 
real grasp of what each man is doing.

IMO in a well trained army the requirement for each man to be able to 
think and excercise initiative will become greater, not less in the 
future, better communications notwithstanding. In my (admittedly 
limited) experience over control by higher echelons, even when they 
_actually_ have real-time data, does not generally improve performance -
 in fact just the opposite.


