    'body' => '>
>I agree, at this point, that the times should be restricted. All I
>was saying is that If it is known that the ship was stolen, even if
>it more than 16 months away, then the law should allow for enough
>time for the owner to get there. I would think that the fact a ship
>had been stolen would not be something the owner would pay for. It
>would be disminiated by the Imperium to all starports along the jump
>routes and then as ships went elsewhere, they would take it to
>the ports off the routes. Again, YMMV.
>
Consider this: a merchant ship of J2 can, on a misjump, wind up up to 18
jumps away. A J2 ship can cross the rift, if she\'s got enough demountable
tankage.

In either case, it is likely that the ship could be sold well before any
news of it being stolen is possible. Likewise, a legitimate trader can be
over 4 months each way commo time from it\'s homeworld of Registry, as still
be legit. Especially if paid off. Realistic limits have to be set so that
insurures don\'t justify "Waiting for a response from every planet in the
imperium"; 16 imperial months is sufficient for X-mail from one end to the
other and back, assuming J-4 x-mail [1]. Realistically, a 3 month probate
period allows for any normal operations to have a chance to hear and
respond. it gives 5 X-mail jumps (40 days) out, plus 40 days back, plus 4
days time on target. (3 Imp Months is 84 days, BTW). So every world within
4J4 gets the message, essentially, plus the main line gets it. That\'s
within reasonable range. Requiring recovery within a year increases trade:
If the ship isn\'t recovered, the insurance must write it off 3 months later
as non-recoverable, and replace it. The bank can either write it off or
replace it. Mind you, any ship wich can get far enough away that 5 Xmail
hops won\'t get there has been striving hard to get out of dodge, since it\'s
made some. Additionally, if a ship gets stolen, and you notify everyone
within 16 months x-mail hops, you\'ve probably out run it. By the time they
have replied, you\'ve got a basic assumption going it\'s not coming back.

Anything longer than one year (Round trip x-mail from captial to the
marches and back, BTW), and you start looking at insurers and banks being
able to hold significant ammounts of trade off by failure to declare a ship
lost, and allow for replacement. Money changing hands is the lifesblood of
the imperium. The easiest way to pay a claim is to recover the ship, yes,
but reasonable times must also be linked to other factors. Note also, I
don\'t limit skip tracing to a year IMTU. Skipping is not the same as theft
of ship; it\'s criminal breach of contract.

Any system is going to allow for scamming. Heck, the existing systems for
earth don\'t actually define "abandoned" all that well. The most common
definition I\'ve seen is "All crew left either on the captain\'s orders or
voluntarily, while at sea, without arranging for the ship to be under tow
or otherwise defended or recovered". SO if you abandon ship, and haven\'t
already called for a recovery, it\'s fair game. Different nations have
differing standards for abandoned. The US salvaged a sunk russian sub
(well, part of it) at one point. The russians couldn\'t do much about it,
either. It had become a derelict, within a year of going down. Note also
the sub had gone down without encoutering direct enemy action.

