    'body' => '"Jason T. Barnabas" <cybernaut@netzero.net> wrote:
> With all the modern technology available, I\'m surprised
> that someone hasn\'t integrated a computer with voice
> recognition software.  You talk to in the mic just like
> normal, the computer digitally records your words and
> sends it out at say 56 K.  

56K??? I think the person using such a system would be 
easy enough to track from the gigantic piece of wire they\'ll
be lugging around.

The average digital cell phone transmits at between 8 and 13
kbps - it takes a _lot_ of bandwidth to transmit high bit-rates
over the air. Remember that any piece of copper has as much
bandwidth as the rest of the universe combined and there\'s
a hell of a lot more competition for wireless bandwidth.
(Assuming you\'re the sole user of the piece of wire).

At any rate, your suggestion is a good one, which
is why modern CDMA cell phone technology (used by Sprint
in the US and Bell & Clearnet in Canada, among others) is
derived from military technology, spread spectrum (and a
bunch of other things, but there\'s a lot of similarity
between spread spectum and code division multiplexing).

Better yet, you can record voice as low as 4k per second 
(and still understand it) and transmit at higher rates,
making the burst pretty short.

The best part about CDMA transmission is that they look
just like noise - *mathematically*. An observer without
a connection into the transmission system (ie. either the
base or handset) can\'t tell whether it\'s a cell phone
or a leaky microwave. (Well, they probably could, but it
would be a lot easier to trick than the typical analog
AMPS-type cell phone, which can be monitored with a $20
piece of hardware from Radio Shack).

> Even with a redundant copy to
> verify from, a two minute report would take less than a
> 10th of a second to transmit.  While there would be a lag
> time of the same length as the time it takes you to say
> your piece, I would imagine that the safety factor would
> more than make up for the annoyance factor.  Well, it
> would for me anyhow.

Hm, well, again, you could cut the transmission time to
one half or one third of the original, but you\'d need to
suck up a few gigahertz of bandwidth to do it in a tenth
of a second. That would probably stand out pretty obviously.

The best part is that this is all derived from Shannon\'s
law which limits information transfer rates - something
that the Third Imperium is unlikely to circumvent. (Although
finding a way around Shannon\'s law would be pretty cool...
compressing the sum of human knowledge into two bytes :)

Ethan, behind on digests
