    'body' => '>On 9 Dec 99, at 15:39, Douglas E. Berry wrote:
>
>> The basic load for an Imperial Army infantryman comes in at about 40lbs.
>> The basic weapon (4mm Gauss Rifle) has fairly heavy ammo, and they were
>> Combat Enviroment Suits. --
>
>What exactly do you mean by basic load? In NZ we have no such beast.
>
Basic load: The basic field issue load-out for combat.

Typical (based upon my limited experience with infantry, and the Soldier\'s
Manual of Common Tasks, aka Smart Book):

1 kg load bearing equipment (Belt, suspenders, and pouches)
2 kg field pack
2-4 kg battle rifle or assault rifle (empty)
1 kg bayonet
1 kg Entrenching tool
1 kg medical supplies
2 kg change of uniform
4 kg MOPP gear, not including L4 suit (Includes boots, gloves, and mask)
2 kg MOPP Coverall (The L4 suit)
1-5 kg Basic load of ammunition: (US ARMY: 4-7 clips of ammo, plus 2-8
grenades)
0.5 kg Flashlight
0.5 kg Poncho
1 kg Shelter half
0.5 kg underwear (Socks, shorts, shirts) for 3-7 changes)
2-4 kg Rations, MRE
4.2 kg water (4 L in two canteens)
- ----
25-35 kg total, for moving out on foot.

Patrol BL (based off of SMART book and what I\'ve seen of the US Army in
Bosnia, Somalia, Iraq, and Germany from news footage):
1 kg load bearing equipment (Belt, suspenders, and pouches)
2-4 kg battle rifle or assault rifle (empty)
1 kg bayonet
1 kg Entrenching tool
1 kg medical supplies
2 kg MOPP mask
1-5 kg Basic load of ammunition: (US ARMY: 4-7 clips of ammo, plus 2-8
grenades)
0.5 kg Flashlight
0.5 kg Poncho
4.2 kg water (4 L in two canteens)
- ----
14-20 kg total daily carry.

Almost every soldier in the field carrys the basic load. (Some officers
don\'t, but they also tend to be REMFs.)

E-tools, if clean, also make decent skillets. They serve as a (poor)
shovel, axe, and single-leg camp-stool; they fold to 10cm x 20cm x 5 cm.

Commo, medic, and Squad Support Weapon people carry more. Most infantry
also carry ammo for the SSW trooper. Light Foot Arty (Mortars) also have
much higher basic loads. The NZA might not call it a basic load, but I
guarantee the regulars have a basic load under some identity. It\'s contents
may differ. Specific weights may vary. But there is in almost every modern
army a basic soldier\'s rerquired carry for the field, and that is the basic
load.

