>>
>>I can\'t remember if the Union call them Azi, but they do rely on vat
>>grown workers. _Serpent\'s Reach_ had Azi, and Chondrin (near immortals)
>>and hive minds called Marjat (something like that, anyway).
>
> Union call them \'Azi\'. They\'re covered in depth in \'Cyteen\' and 
> \'40,000 in Gehenna\'.

> Overall I\'d disagree with Leonard\'s view on Union - reading the 
> books, Union increasingly becomes more human (\'than human\') whilst 
> Alliance and Earth move towards totalitarianism. Union\'s reliance on 
> Azi stems from the fact they are initially relying on their Vat grown 
> people to combat the shear numbers available to the Earth Company, 
> dominating as it does the mother well.
>
> I\'d agree that Union is \'alien\' during the Company War, particularly 
> because of the similarities between Azi as a result of Deep tape 
> learning.

There\'s at least one other story that is *very* instructive. It has a
bored "real human" gambling with an Azi. And at some point the Azi
starts sneaking sessions with tapes intended for his "mistress". And
finally, he is "freed". But it takes a *long* look at an issue that the
typical "human" in the Union didn\'t want to. What *is* the difference
between "humans" and Azi. *Are* azi "real people" (even if Union law
and customs says they aren\'t). 

Also, I think "40,000 in Gehenna" shows a glimpse of a *truly* alien
culture. Nobody who has read that book is going to claim that a
Gehennan is "human" in any sense except genetically. 

Having a few minor human races (ok, *cultures*) around that are *more*
alien than any of Traveller\'s aliens is a good way to shake people up,
but it won\'t be easy. 

Several of Cherryh\'s books are good sources for such "alien humans". So
is Donald Kingsbury\'s "Courtship Rite". I know there are others, but I
can\'t think of titles at the moment. 

