>from that cause.

Carbon 14 dating can be inaccurate see:
http://www.parentcompany.com/creation_explanation/cx8j.htm
In one case a sample of coal was dated as 1,680 years old and was really 
about 100,000,000 years old.

It\'s probably not the Carbon that\'s causing the problem. Coal in it\'s 
natural form contains a small amount of both Uranium and Thorium. When the 
coal is burnt this is released as both a gas and a solid.

Even if the uranium and thorium have decayed two of their products are 
Radium and Radon.

It\'s these elements that prevent Sellafield from having a coal power 
station.

>The above does not imply that I know what the source of carbon 14 in the
>environment is.

Carbon 14 is created in the upper atmosphere by the action of cosmic rays on 
carbon 12 atoms (usually in the form of carbon dioxide). Plants take in the 
Carbon dioxide during photosythesis and so carbon 14 gets into the food 
chain.

Speaking of photosynthesis:
The photosynthesis process requires chlorofil to be present for the 
convertion from carbon dioxide to oxygen. Does this mean that all plants on 
all Traveller planets with oxygen/carbon dioxide atmospheres are green. Or 
is it possible to substitute chlorofil for another substance and end up with 
blue/red/any colour plants that perform the same function?

J.

