    'from' => 'jonathanlupton@hotmail.com',
    'body' => '>Introducing new players to the OTU can be a bit of a worry.

Trying to introduce single players into an existing game is difficult 
enough. With Traveller the chances are you\'ll be starting with all/nearly 
all the players being new to the background and game system.

I think a good way to start is to run the first session based in a single 
system. Pick a simple pre-published adventure, create a set of characters 
from one service and read out an introduction to the adventure that leads 
them up to the start of the action.

Run several one-off\'s along these lines and introduce each service one at a 
time introducing new concepts in each adventure. After about three of these 
you should be in a possition for people to choose their own characters and 
to start the campaign proper.

For Example:
First session run Shadows with a group of scouts sent to survey the planet. 
Read a paragraph or two describing their arrival at the system landing and 
refueling at the starport and then dump them in the action.

Second session run a Murder Mystery aboard a Subsidised Liner the players 
should be the crew (allow one to play a noble or other passenger). Have the 
captain as an NPC and order the PC crew to do the tasks aboard the ship. 
This adventure should introduce the concepts behind running a starship and 
travelling from system to system.

Third session introduce some combat with a navy patrol ship and some marines 
in a space combat/boarding action.......

After these three games the players should have a reasonable idea of 
possible characters and have an overview of the way the traveller universe 
works. You can then introduce details like alien races, etc as the game 
progresses.

J.

