    'subj' => 'RE: Starting Traveller Newbies, Handouts',
    'from' => 'jonathanlupton@hotmail.com',
    'body' => '>	Somebody mentioned handouts, and I am a big fan of those.
>	I like to start new players slowly, possibly as hirelings
>	who don\'t make any big decisions.  It might even be possible
>	to role-play some missions from the PCs character generation.
>	Naturally, giving the players hints at appropriate moments
>	can help to get things going, perhaps through a helpful NPC.

TSR went through a phase of producing "flip books" for their Dark Sun
adventures. The adventure came with a book of pictures to show the players 
at specified points during the adventure. Unfortunately TSR made a few 
mistakes (Jungle pictures in a desert scene, giving the plot away at the 
start of the adventure etc.) and the idea was dropped.

One of the best systems for handouts was Warhammer FRP particularly the 
Enemy Within Campaign. These adventures contained lots of letters, maps and 
clues that the PC\'s collect during the adventures. Some of the handouts 
contained obscure clues that would only make sense further along in the 
campaign, the players have to reference back to older handouts to follow the 
entire plot (it was entirely possible to play the adventures and suceed and 
never work out what was really going on).

The use of pictures and handouts can remove alot of the descriptive work 
required by the GM and help prevent misunderstandings. The only problem is 
the time taken to produce them can be a bit too much for a GM. I think many 
of the published adventures for lots of game systems would benefit from more 
handouts.

J.

