    'topic' => ' GURPS Aliens (NOT GT Alien Races) in Traveller',
    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'eg798',
    'body' => 'Jeff Zeitlin writes:
> I\'d be interested in seeing various listmembers critiques of
> GURPS Aliens, in the context of using them in Traveller.  How
> well do the various races fit into a Traveller campaign, and how
> would they have to be modified to fit?  Which ones would you run
> as a player, and which ones would you allow as a referee - and
> why?  How do you feel the existence and/or influence of any of
> these races would affect the \'feel\' of Imperial culture? And,
> what other thoughts do you have about them as pertains to
> Traveller?

Ok, running through them in semi-random order:
*An Phar: minor race, no special comments.
*Aurora: traditional plot device aliens.  This role tends to be filled by
 Ancient artifacts, but no reason not to toss an Aurora into the mix.  They 
 should be _much_ less well-known than is suggested by their description, 
 though.
*Banduch: the role of \'mysterious psionic aliens\' is mostly already filled by
 the Droyne, but they could show up on a redzoned world well enough.
*Cidi: I personally do not like \'sentient tribbles\', but YMMV.
*Crystal Computers: redzone bait, but no mods needed in that role.
*Engai: having a mysterious alien race where old members of the race recall the
 Ancients (personally) is likely to do some violence to the history of the OTU.
 However, they could make for a fairly neat plot device.
*Fasanni: with their advantages, the Fasanni, once they show up in space, are
 likely to spread widely and fairly rapidly.  As such, once they show up in the
 campaign they should gradually become more and more common, sort of without
 being noticed...
*Gerodians: basically a minor human race.  Super-intelligent alien races are
 almost always a bad thing, though. 
*Gloworms: more redzone bait.
*Gormelites: does your traveller universe _really_ need wookies?  Their world
 is likely to be red or amber zoned, they\'re kind of dangerous to interact
 with.
*Irari: with a group of super-intelligent compulsive researchers around, one
 would expect TLs to rise a bit faster than they do.
*Jaril: perfectly fine minor race
*Kaa: the Kaa personality is not suited to a minor race.  To really use them as
 they are written up in G:Aliens they should be a major race with territory
 comparable to other major races.  With minor adjustments they could be a minor
 hostile state on the boarders of the Imperium.
*Kronin: basically a minor human race with a weird society.  Could be placed by
 themselves on a redzoned world.
*Liook Sujan: red-zone bait.  Of course, they\'re sufficiently inobvious that
 they could turn out to be present on just about any lightly populated world,
 and are thus Plot Devices.
*Markann: Having a TL 14 hostile alien race moving about in the Imperium would
 be fairly destructive to the stability of the Imperium, though there\'s nothing
 really wrong with using them anyway (nothing says the Imperium needs to be
 stable).  Not suitable to PCs, and their introduction would not be a minor
 plot point.
*Mmm: instant red-zone.  The ability of Mmm drones to communicate at unlimited
 distances would be very destructive to the Traveller setting.
*Memer and Saret: reasonable minor alien race.
*Pachekki: fine minor race.
*Purulu: likely to be confined to a single world; hard to use as written, the
 Imperium is sufficiently racist that the Purulu wouldn\'t be able to get away
 with their truly annoying personality traits.
*Riders: Plot device.  If they are known, they could create major paranoia in
 the Imperium.  Of course, Imperial biotech is unimpressive.  Probably a bad
 idea for PCs, though.
*Sparrials: tolerable minor race.
*Tamile: \'primitive\' is unclear in the Traveller setting.  Tamile would be an
 interesting encounter in a Far Trader campaign, otherwise probably not useful.
*Traders: the sort of thing which would be likely to be a huge issue once it
 showed up.  If I were using them I\'d probably have them appear _only_ in
 J-space (and replace their vulnerability to metal with a dependency on
 J-space).  Having giant trading ships suddenly enter your jump envelope and
 start trading would be amusing...
*Treefolk: not a race I\'m particularly fond of, but an ok minor race.
*Verms: possible red zone bait.  Verms really aren\'t powerful enough to be a
 threat to most people, though; if you want to use them I\'d up their abilities
 dramatically.
*Xenomorphs: see Riders.
'
