That\'s putting it mildly.

Carbon-14 dating is a rigorously validated means of measuring the age of
organic materials within the age ranges it handles well (this is
dependent on the size of the sample, as the larger the sample, the
larger detectable amount of C-14 is present, the older the sample can be
dated.)

HOWEVER, the technique does not differentiate between carbon deposited
while the organic material was alive and carbon deposits laid down on or
in the sample later (colonization by fungi and bacteria, foex), and
since the typical samples come from rather complexly contaminated sites
(aka \'dug up out of the ground\'), proper sample handling is paramount
for an accurate result.

Those \'inaccurate\' dating citations on that creationist website are all
examples of poor sample aquisition, bad handling technique, or using the
technique outside of it\'s intended range of application, and do not
stand up as criticisms of the method.

Crappy technique <> wrong science.

