    'topic' => ' Nobility',
    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

William wrote:
>>   There is an interesting article in one of the Traveller Chronicle <10 by
>>Andy Slack(?)  dealing with the extension of social standing from A-Z that
>>way filling plenty of room for lots of noble ranks.  It is really a first
>>class piece of writing.
>
>It also totally changes the feel of the setting (I\'ve tried it). I\'d
>suggest avoiding it... but it is wonderfully written. It also is not
>supportive of existing canon. Great for Heresy, though.

There has been a few discussions of Nobility on this list, and the subject of
how you organise noble titles with a vast population of nobles has arisen
before. There seem to be two main options proposed:
     1. Increase the number of noble ranks past "F";
     2. Distinguish between local nobility and Imperial nobility.

I\'d call the first option the the quick and dirty approach. It may work, but has
drawbacks - mainly due to its simplicity. The second option, I think is the
better - and more canonical - one.

Note that the term "local nobility" can be confusing. Here\'s the canon (boom!):
"Local nobility represents the Imperium in systems not administered by high
nobility. These nobles make up the majority of the Imperial nobility, and
although they are only equivalent to barons and knights in precedence, they are
hereditary members of the peerage."

This allows the second option to be drawn out a number of interesting ways.
First, the local nobility can have local titles that sound more impressive (ie.
higher in precedence) than their Imperial title. Heaven forbid if you address
them by the "lower" Imperial title in the context of their own local
jurisdiction - and conversely, you would never find them officially addressed as
anything other than their Imperial title when off-world (or at least out of
their local context).

If you are worried that this makes the Imperial bureaucracy look too telescoped
together, think of it like this: Cleon _imposed_ this system on the Sylean
Federation. He is portrayed as being a canny politician, so you could suppose
that he made up a system that is simple enough to keep track of (ie. has only a
few levels), but has complicated-enough qualification rules that keep the new
(and intendent) nobility quarrelling about their comparative status rather than
seriously vying for the Throne itself.

What you can also suppose is that extra-Imperial worlds used to have local
nobility or rulers with fanciful titles ("tzar", "emir", "king", "potentate",
etc etc). When these worlds were integrated into the Imperium, the local ruler
was either given a place in the high nobility with an imperial title (such as
Marquis, the ruler of a single world), or simply retain their local title but
are only considered - in Imperial precedence - as equal to an Imperial Baron.
The only local title that the Imperium would frown upon keeping is that of
"emperor" (a bit like the army captain being brevetted to "Major" aboard a naval
vessel - you can only have _one_ of those aboard ship, y\'know... ;-)

This enables you to have a universe which, like reality, is not cut-and-dried.
Entire campaigns could revolve around proving that one local noble line should
be granted Imperial stature, or hunting down the correct lineage of a noble
family, or performing such tasks for a noble patron that are designed at raising
their Imperial precedence.

There you go, Loren! Three adventure seeds for the new book! ;-)
