    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>> Actually carbon is radioactive, this property is used when carbon
>> dating an item. You measure the ratio of carbon 14 to carbon 12 the
>> more carbon 14 you have the newer it is. Carbon has a long half life
>> (it decays slowly) but would still set the sensors off at
>> Sellafield.  And you wouldn\'t want to be there if it did!

> Um, Carbon-14 has a 5700 year half life. Since the coal deposits are over
> 100 million years old (460 million comes to mind) there is no problem
> from that cause.
>
> IIRC, carbon 14 dating assumes that the living matter is continually
> absorbing carbon 14 from the environment. A process that stops as soon as
> the thing dies.

Which is why one of the "Biblical literalist" arguments against carbon
dating is such a bad joke. They gleefully point out that a sample from
a plastic comb reads as half a million years old. 

Well, actually, it readfs out as "older than we can measure". Which is
reasonable enough given that the carbon in plastics comes from coal or
oil and has thus been dead for milions of years. <sigh>

> The above does not imply that I know what the source of carbon 14 in the
> environment is.

Cosmic rays converted N-14 to C-14 at a fairly steady rate. Tree ring
matching has let them calibrate the scale back to around 10,000 BC.
There aren\'t any trees that old, but they can match growth patterns in
the inner rings of old trees with patterns in the outer rings of
stumps. Then you match the pattens in the inner parts of those with
older stumps. 

From this, they\'ve determined that the cosmic ray flux *does vary
measurably on thousand year timescales.

- -- 
