    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Speaking of photosynthesis:
> The photosynthesis process requires chlorofil to be present for the 
> convertion from carbon dioxide to oxygen. Does this mean that all plants on 
> all Traveller planets with oxygen/carbon dioxide atmospheres are green. Or 
> is it possible to substitute chlorofil for another substance and end up with 
> blue/red/any colour plants that perform the same function?

There are organisms on *earth* that use something other than
chlorphyll. But they tend to be "primitive algae, as chlorophyll is
*very* efficient, even though it reflects light near the peak of Sol\'s
light output curve. 

But with different stars and different environments, other chemicals
*are* possible. 

