> Josh W. Spencer writes:
>>Hello.
>>This is probably considered an easy question: Does any ship
>>maintain its original velocity and vector when exiting jumpspace?
>
>         Easy, no.  Thoroughly discussed on the TML, yes.  Opinions
>         vary, but some of the issues raised: Stars are moving relative
>         to each other, should this velocity be included?  Planets are
>         moving around stars, should this movement be included?

If momentum is conserved by jump, then your velocity upon entering jump
*relative to a given object* will be the same as your velocity upon
exiting jump relative to the *same* object. Thus the question about "do
planetary orbital velocities count" is irrelevant. 

If you measured relative to the planet you left, then on exit you\'d
measure relative to the position and velocity the planet had when you
jumped, not it\'s current velocity and position (both of which have
changed in the intervening week). 


>  Can
>         freetraders accelerate all the way to 100 diameters, then jump
>         so that they will arrive headed into their destination planet?
>         (this would make intercepting ships at 100D very difficult)

Don\'t forget that the time you spend in jump *varies*. That means that
if you aimed for a spot at the 100 diameter limit of the destination,
but emerged a day early (or a day late) the planet will be a *long*
ways away. For example, earth orbit\'s the sun at 30 km/sec. So in 24
hours it moves 2.6 *million* km. That\'s several hours away in normal
space. 

>         My own take is that velocity is conserved if you jump into
>         deep space (no substantial masses present), but the closer
>         that you are to a mass when you come out of jump, the closer
>         you are to conserving velocity /relative to that mass/.

Which doesn\'t help, because conservation of momentum requires that the
before and after values be measured in the *same* reference frame. If
you teleport from earth (at rest with respect to Earth) and arrive at
rest with respect to Mars, you have to explain what happened to the
difference between the orbital velocities of Earth and Mars. You also
have to explain what happened to the difference in potential energy
(Earth is a lot deeper in the sun\'s gravity well and the surface of
Mars has a potential in it\'s *own* gravity well that\'s equvalent to
being one hell of a long ways above the surface of the Earth. And then
there\'s the differences in angular momentum. 

>         This has the practical effect that if you leave Regina at
>         25 km/sec (relative to Regina), you arrive at Ruie moving at
>         25 km/sec (relative to Ruie).  Of course, if the PCs want
>         more detail, the velocity at Ruie might be 25.02 km/sec if
>         the arrival distance from Ruie is different from the departure
>         distance from Regina (I include a large random element to
>         arrival location).

Alas, since the two planets are almost certainly moving at different
velocities relative to each other, this *doesn\'t* solve the problem.
You still have to account for *that* velocity difference. 

In other words. you pick a reference point at the *start* of a
calculation and you have to keep measuring relative to that *point*
during the entire calculation. Since planets are moving in *curved*
paths, you can\'t use them as the reference point for any calculation
covering a period during which the change in the planet\'s velocity
vector is significant. It\'s *definitely* significant over a week!

On the other hand, while stars are orbiting the galaxy, their orbits
are so long that *stellar* motion (in non-binary systems) can be
considered to be "striaght line" over periods of *years*. In binary
systems you use the center of mass of the system as the reference
point. 

So you can measure the ship\'s before and after velocity using one of
the star\'s as a reference point (or even a third star). This means you
need to know how fast and in what direction the stars are moving
relative to each other, and how fast the ship was moving relative to
the reference star. 

If it comes out of jump with the same velocity, then you get to convert
that into velocity relative to the target star. And then into velocity
relative to the target planet. 

Simplest dodge is to assume the stars are stationary with respect to
each other. In actuality, they might be moving at 50 km/sec relative to
each other. Give or take 10 or 20 km/sec. :-)

Then you have to worry about motion of the planets. Since Traveller
uses "flat" maps so much, we might as well assume that the orbital
planes of the planets are aligned. It makes for easier calculations,
that\'s for sure!

So now you need to worry about *where* in it\'s orbit the planet is.
After all, in midsummer it\'s moving with the same speed as in
midwinter(well, usually), but in the *opposite* direction.

And the same goes for the destination planet. And it\'s unlikely to have
the same length year. 

It\'s actually fairly *easy* to add up all these velocity vectors.  Just
take a sheet of paper and *draw* the first vector. Make a starting
point and draw an arrow in the proper direction, with a length equal to
the speeds (say 1 mm for every km/sec of speed). So if the planet is
moving 30 km/sec at a 45 degree angle to rimward, draw a 30 mm line at
a 45 degree angle to which ever direction on the paper you\'ve decided
rimward is. Now, let\'s say the second planet is moving at 23 km/sec at
75 degrees to rimward. You place the ruler at the *point* of the first
arrow, and lay it at 75 degrees to the rimward direction, then draw an
arrow 23 mm long. Finally, lay the ruler between the *start* of the
first arrow and the *end* of the second one. The speed is the distance
between those points. And the direction is the direction of the line
between them. 

If there are more vectors (say you have the stars moving relative to
each other) just add them in as more arrows. Just be sure that each new
arrow has its start (tail) at the *head* of the previous arrow, and
that you measure angles relative to the *same* side of the paper for
all the arrows. Then just draw a line from the tail of the first arrow
to the head of the last, and that\'s the sum of all those vectors. 

Believe me, it\'s one *hell* of a lot simpler than trying to *calculate*
all of the vectors!

