    'body' => '> >I have rarely used Traveler rules for roleplaying , as I don\'t like using
> >rules for roleplaying even with goood rules, and in general Traveler
rules
> >are not good for actual playing (though they\'re great as a basis for
> >character creation, ship design and wargaming )
>
> The rules of any roleplaying game should be a basis for resolving those
> bits which are NOT "Role Played". By by that standard, the rest of the
> followingg makes little sense...

Yeah, sorry, I said that badly, what I meant is that as soon as you have to
start using the rule system for combat, especially space combat,  and such
it tends to bog down.

<snip>
> JC is a wonderfully written game. It has a decent set of rules; a simple
> and consistant mechanic. The mechanics are a hybrid of tactical wargame
and
> roleplaying skill systems. The vehicle design system is more a rating
> system, which also tells you how big it MUST be (as a range), based upon
> the basic tech level of the system. Not to mention it is compatable with
> Heavy Gear and Tribe 8.

No argument there.

>But, the system overall, while well written and
> simple, looks to lend it self more to dice-rolling than role-playing. (I
> have not yet run any of the DP9 stuff except as solo-combat bits).

The thing I liked about it was that just using the system as written (i.e;
without having to fudge it ) we managed to run a space battle between two
squadrons of mechs and fighters in about forty minutes.

I\'ve tried similar things in Traveller, and we had to basically ignore the
starship combat rules to get anything useful done in a reasonable time. Not
that this is unusual, I suspect most people don\'t use the starship combat
rules unless they\'re specifically looking for a wargame, but the thing is
that in JC you don\'t have to avoid the rules.

And they work to a level of detail that made the roleplaying part fun. The
guy who blew up the enemy mech only to have his own thrusters and most of
the torso of his mech destroyed in the ensuing ammunition explosion. The
enemy mech who lost all thruster control, who we captured and brought home
by tossing him between us like a large football.

Yes, there were quite a few die rolls, but they were simple ones, and so did
not get in the way of the roleplaying part of the combat.

Part of this may have been was the whole idea of fighting in humanoid mechs,
you can\'t give the finger to an enemy while flying a fighter and expect him
to see you, but when you do it in a 30m mech, he\'s likely to get the idea.

There is also a good set of choices in combat for players, making the combat
as much part of the roleplay as everything else, you can characterize by
your combat choices.

However, the JC scenarios do tend to emphasize combat, and don\'t provide a
lot of scope for roleplaying except when "off-duty", or in special
situations, pretty much like the old FASA Star Trek rules and scenarios
didn\'t lend themselves to roleplaying, unless you weren\'t a part of Star
Fleet.

>Best non-FTL RPG setting I\'ve read. Much better than Terradyne.
> Setting with details as rich and mineable for ideas as S1889.
>
> I do agree, however, that it should eb looked at, especially the books on
> ships. Great feel for TL9, extended duration, in-system ships. Note: Trav
> TL 9 is pregravitic, and late TL 9 is jump capable.

Yeah, which is exactly why I went for this period with this JC/T2300 mix, as
T2300 can give me all the near star info and planetary descriptions, the
Kafers, etc, and T2300 actually does have mechs, though not quite as big and
versatile as the JC ones.

The big differences will be the political set-up, as JC doesn\'t have the
same political background. But as I\'m running around the "First interstellar
flight" time, that won\'t matter much.

Frankie
