    'index' => 'eg929',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'Leonard Erickson writes:
>>Chlorophyll is the most important photosynthetic pigment
>>found here on Terra, but there are other pigments involved
>>in many species.  The various colours that leaves take on
>>in the fall, in temperate climes, are caused by these
>>pigments.
>Those pigments are always there, but they *don\'t* take part in
>photosynthesis. 

	From Life, the science of biology (Purves et al, 1992):
	"Here we discuss pigments that play roles in
	photosynthesis... Of these, the most important are the
	chlorophylls." "...all photosynthetic organisms possess
	accessory pigments that absorb photons intermediate in
	energy between the red and blue and then transfer a
	portion of the energy to chlorophyll..."  Interestingly
	enough, while all known Terran photosynthetic organisms
	have accessory pigments (such as carotenoids and
	phycobilins), not all of them have chlorophyll.
	Photosynthetic halobacteria use a derivative of retinol,
	called bacteriorhodopsin, rather than chlorophyll.

>>I would expect to see photosynthetic structures
>>of different colours, depending on the wavelengths of light
>>that arrive.
>Wavelength isn\'t as important as you\'d think. Remember,
>chlorophyll is green because it *reflects* green light. And
>that\'s practically at the peak of Sol\'s emmission spectrm (ie
>the strongest single wavelngth in the mix).

	Peak wavelength of absorption for chlorophyll a is about
	430 nm (blue-violet) with a lesser peak at 670 nm (red),
	for chlorophyll b the peaks are at 455 nm (blue-green)
	and 640 nm (red-orange) respectively.  The overall 
	perception of light that is not absorbed (including 
	primarily violet, green, yellow, orange, and red light)
	is green.  Accessory pigments absorb light effectively
	at other wavelengths, but green light is absorbed less
	than most other visible wavelengths.  The net result is
	that photosynthetic machinery is better at using some
	wavelengths than others: this varies by species, but in
	a water plant (/Anacharis/) efficiency is highest for about
	430 nm (deep blue) and 680 nm (red-orange), with a low
	around 550 nm (yellow-green), and it almost ceases at
	about 725 nm (near infra-red).  Since the photosynthetic
	machinery depends so much on the wavelength of available
	light, it is fair to say that wavelength is important.

Peez
