    'ts-index' => '1999-12-14.eg931',
    'body' => 'Leonard Erickson writes:
>>Josh W. Spencer writes:
>>>This is probably considered an easy question: Does any ship
>>>maintain its original velocity and vector when exiting jumpspace?
>>Easy, no.  Thoroughly discussed on the TML, yes.  Opinions
>>vary, but some of the issues raised: Stars are moving relative
>>to each other, should this velocity be included?  Planets are
>>moving around stars, should this movement be included?
>If momentum is conserved by jump, then your velocity upon entering
>jump *relative to a given object* will be the same as your velocity
>upon exiting jump relative to the *same* object. Thus the question
>about "do planetary orbital velocities count" is irrelevant. 

	If velocity is conserved relative to the star, then the 
	orbital movement of the planet can certainly be relevent.

>If you measured relative to the planet you left, then on exit
>you\'d measure relative to the position and velocity the planet had
>when you jumped, not it\'s current velocity and position (both of
>which have changed in the intervening week).

	That depends entirely on how you want to bend the physics.
	You may do as you like IYTU.

>>Can
>>freetraders accelerate all the way to 100 diameters, then jump
>>so that they will arrive headed into their destination planet?
>>(this would make intercepting ships at 100D very difficult)
>Don\'t forget that the time you spend in jump *varies*.

	That is what most people assume.  I allow some variation,
	but not anything like a day.

>That means that if you aimed for a spot at the 100 diameter
>limit of the destination, but emerged a day early (or a day late)
>the planet will be a *long* ways away. For example, earth orbit\'s
>the sun at 30 km/sec. So in 24 hours it moves 2.6 *million* km.
>That\'s several hours away in normal space.

	This argument only works if "jumpspace" works in a certain
	way.  IMTU, masses such as planets warp jumpspace and
	influence reentry into normal space.  Thus, there is a
	tendency to come out close to the planet.  Even so, it is
	not unknown for ships to arrive much further than 2.6 million
	km from their destination (depending on pilot and nav skills,
	various DMs, etc.) IMTU.  This is not a problem for me.

>>My own take is that velocity is conserved if you jump into
>>deep space (no substantial masses present), but the closer
>>that you are to a mass when you come out of jump, the closer
>>you are to conserving velocity /relative to that mass/.
>Which doesn\'t help, because conservation of momentum requires
>that the before and after values be measured in the *same*
>reference frame.

	Doesn\'t help what?  It helps me, my game, my players.  You
	see, none of them are jump-space physicists  :)

If you teleport from earth (at rest with respect to Earth) and
>arrive at rest with respect to Mars
<snipped>

	I don\'t  :)

>>This has the practical effect that if you leave Regina at
>>25 km/sec (relative to Regina), you arrive at Ruie moving at
>>25 km/sec (relative to Ruie).  Of course, if the PCs want
>>more detail, the velocity at Ruie might be 25.02 km/sec if
>>the arrival distance from Ruie is different from the departure
>>distance from Regina (I include a large random element to
>>arrival location).
>Alas, since the two planets are almost certainly moving at
>different velocities relative to each other, this *doesn\'t*
>solve the problem. You still have to account for *that*
>velocity difference. 

	I think that the difficulty here is that you are trying to
	solve a different problem than I.  You seem to be trying to
	work out the most realistic solution given our present
	understanding of physics.  I have no problem with that,
	but it is not what I am trying to do.  I am well aware of
	the "frame of reference" issue, but I want to play Traveller.
	If it turns out that the most reasonable scenario, given our
	current understanding of physics, invalidates the TU, then
	I will postulate a revolution in physics.  I can live with
	the combat system and a flat universe, I can live with a few
	radical new insights into physics  :)

<interesting approach to jump vectors snipped>

Peez
