    'from' => 'Kyle Schuant kyle3054@yahoo.com',
    'body' => 'Jonathan wanted to know:
> Speaking of photosynthesis:
> The photosynthesis process requires chlorofil to be
> present for the 
> convertion from carbon dioxide to oxygen. Does this
> mean that all plants on 
> all Traveller planets with oxygen/carbon dioxide
> atmospheres are green. Or 
> is it possible to substitute chlorofil for another
> substance and end up with 
> blue/red/any colour plants that perform the same
> function?

Kyle asked some friends in bilogy and they told him:
Well, we expect alien worlds to have alien
biochemistries, so make up what you like. In terms of
what already exists on earth, though, the human body,
for example, processes a small amount of sunlight, and
these compounds have no real colour. You could also
postulate a world with higher than earth levels of UV
radiation, so that plants must get a "tan", ie have a
protective coloured coating to stop the chlorophyll
being degraded. Additionally, photosynthesis may be
dominant here, but not on other worlds. Here on earth
in deep ocean trenches there are plants that survive
on heat (since no light can get there), called,
believe it or not, "thermosynthesis". Surely similar
plants could exist on the surface of a world? And
there\'s no colour restrictions.
For an interesting story of an alien ecology and some
earth colonists\' interaction with it, see, Larry Niven
and Jerry Pournelle\'s, "The Legacy of Heorot." I
highly recommend it.

