Based upon what I was taught while a history major:

A Civil War is when one government temporarily becomes two or more, and
they war with each other.

A Revolution is when one government becomes two or more, and go to war,
with at least two of the governments surviving at the close of hostilities.

A Rebellion is when subjects of one government try to replace it by force.

A Coup is when a Government is replaced by another government. Sometimes
the result of a Civil War, sometimes politics alone.

Ob Trav: The Solomani Rim War is definitely not a civil war. It resulted
from two extant governments having their ties severed with force. The
Confed was  (pre SRW) the Solomani Autonomous Region. It was a subject
government... and it was, in a sense, a rebellion, but not really a civil
war.

Ob US: The US War of independance was a revolution... The two governments
that resulted have remained independant.... but it was a rebellion as well.

Ahh, the joys of the innaccuracies of the English language, and the prolems
of Jargon...

