I think you forgot the 20% down payment mentioned above.

A=p*(1+(r/n)^nt   compound interest formula (I found it on one of my
		  math "cheat sheets")
A=total amount paid
p=principal (80% of price in our case)
r=rate of interest (%/yr)
t=time (number of years)
n=number of periods per year

A=(80 MCr/240)*480=160 MCr
p=80 MCr
r=???
t=40
n=12

160=80*(1+(r/12))^480

Obviously, (1+(r/12))^480 must equal 2.
2=(1+(r/12))^480
take the 480th root
root480(2)=1+(r/12)
root480(2)-1=r/12
12*(root480(2)-1)=r
r is approximately 1.7%

Alas, this *doesn\'t* jibe with the idea that each 10 years of payments
gets an additional 20% of the ship paid for. So it looks like the
Imperium uses *simple* interest on ship purchase.

Ok, let\'s try *that*.

(I\'ll skip the calculation)

r=2.5%

That\'s a *bit* better. 

So for simple interest, here are the relevant formulas:

I=interest paid (total)
P=principal (amount borrowed)
S=total amount paid (I+P)
r=interest rate (5% = 0.05)
t=time expressed in years
p=monthly payment

I=Prt

S=P+Prt

p=(P+Prt)/(t*12)

So if you pay extra at some point *and the mortage allows it* then you
can recalculate payments from the above.

