    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Leonard Erickson writes:
>>>Josh W. Spencer writes:
>
>>If you measured relative to the planet you left, then on exit
>>you\'d measure relative to the position and velocity the planet had
>>when you jumped, not it\'s current velocity and position (both of
>>which have changed in the intervening week).
>
>         That depends entirely on how you want to bend the physics.
>         You may do as you like IYTU.

I was just trying to make sure that folks understood that conserving
velocity relative to *different* objects *was* "bending physics".

I can accept people bending or breaking the laws of physics in games or
stories. But only if they *know* they are breaking them, and have
thought things thru. Otherwise, the law of unintended consequences
tends to jump out and bite you. :-)


>>>Can
>>>freetraders accelerate all the way to 100 diameters, then jump
>>>so that they will arrive headed into their destination planet?
>>>(this would make intercepting ships at 100D very difficult)
>>Don\'t forget that the time you spend in jump *varies*.
>
>         That is what most people assume.  I allow some variation,
>         but not anything like a day.

It\'s in the rules, at least some editions allow for bout that much
variation. 

>>That means that if you aimed for a spot at the 100 diameter
>>limit of the destination, but emerged a day early (or a day late)
>>the planet will be a *long* ways away. For example, earth orbit\'s
>>the sun at 30 km/sec. So in 24 hours it moves 2.6 *million* km.
>>That\'s several hours away in normal space.
>
>         This argument only works if "jumpspace" works in a certain
>         way.  IMTU, masses such as planets warp jumpspace and
>         influence reentry into normal space.  Thus, there is a
>         tendency to come out close to the planet.  Even so, it is
>         not unknown for ships to arrive much further than 2.6 million
>         km from their destination (depending on pilot and nav skills,
>         various DMs, etc.) IMTU.  This is not a problem for me.

Well, I\'m making the (reasonable, in my opinion) assumption that you
"aim" your jump for a specific *location*. That is, you in effect tell
the computer, we want to go *this* distance, in *that* direction. And
if you don\'t misjump, you exit jump at the target point plus/minus a
bit for uncontrollable "random" factors.

This fits in fairly well with Mark Miller\'s statements that if your
jump "line" intersects the 100 diameter limit of anything between your
entry to jump and your planned exit, you pop out of jump there. 

He hasn\'t answered my question about *when* you pop out of jump. You
see, if you work it out, there could be a planet in the way for only a
few hours. So it matters if those few hours occur when the ship is in
that part of the jump. 

For example, assume that you move along the line at a steady rate. That
means that if the planet is half way, and "hits" the jump line 3.5 days
after you start the jump, you\'d get precipitated out of jump. Except
that means your jump only took 3.5 days.

If you assume "instant" jump, with your ship sitting at the far end
until the "jump buble decays, then the planet crossing the jump line
shouldn\'t affect you unless it crosses the line at the moment you jump.
And if you sit there until 7 days later, you may need a while to find
what it was that dumped you there!

There are a *lot* of unanswered questions, and every answer breeds new
questions. 

Whatever way folks decide to handle things, it needs to be *logical*.
Not merely arbritary decision stacked on top of arbtrary decision. That
leads you into situations where you have to make more and more
arbitrary decisions because *previous* decision have logical
consequences that contradict each other. 

Even non-scientific players start gettung upset when they come up with
clever things that are consistent with what they\'ve been told the rules
are, and get told that it doesn\'t work that way.

BTW, my best reason for going with "real" conservation of momentum,
rather than having it conserved relative to the star/planet at each end
of the jump is that the latter makes it *possible* to run a ship up to
near c velocities then jump it into another system and have a good
chance of being aimed at the target planet. All they have to do is be
aimed at the planet they are jumping from. They\'d come out aimed at the
planet they are jumping to.

If you *don\'t* want that to be possible, then you need the vectors to
work differently, and the easiest way is to use "real" physics.

