The Second amendment says no such thing. it reads:
"A well regulated milita, being necessary to the security of a free State,
the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be infringed."
Ammendment 2 to the US constitution, as presented in "A History of the
United States Since 1856", R. N. Current & G. J. Goodwin, 1980.

It does not specifically enable state militias, nor require that one be in
the "well regulated militia" to keep and bear Arms. note the capitalization
of State. In general, the capitalized singular form refers to a
Nation-State, not to a member of the union, in most interpretations. In a
strictly libertarian view, it becomes enabling for any person to own any
Arms; More realistically, it means that citizens shall be allowed to own
Arms. Interestingly enough, I\'m not aware of any arguments in federal
courts challenging the 2nd ammendment on the basis that Arms (Capitalized)
means Patents of Arms or Achievements of Arms, thus heraldric devisings....
which was still the common terminology at the time written. However, any
who doubt that the framers intended all citizens to bear arms should read
"The Federalist Papers" by Publius. Publius is a pseudonym for Ben Franklin
and Two Other Framers....

