Little known detail. The Supreme court hasn\'t ruled on a second
amendment case since the 30s. And that one doesn\'t really count because
the defendant had died by the time the case got to the court, and his
defense didn\'t submit *any* arguments to the Court.

And in that one the ruling (regarding a law about sawed off shotguns)
was that since it wasn\'t a MILITARILY USEFUL WEAPON it could be
outlawed. A first year law student could have shown that shotguns *are*
"militarily useful", but as I said, the defense lawyers just wanted to
get the case over with.

Since then the court has *refused* to hear any appeals involving the
second amendment. And it\'s part of the law that just because the SC
doesn\'t hear an appeal does *not* indicate that they favor the
arguments of *either* side. 

The only way to *force* them to rule is if two *different* federal
districts make rulings about the same federal law that contradict each
other. So far, in spite of lots of efforts, nobody has managed to pull
it off. 

So all we can determine from the record is that the court hasn\'t ruled
on the matter. Though it seems a *strong* possibility that the court
wants no part of this mess.

Rather like "obscenity". The current standard is showing more and more
holes, mostly because the "community standards" bit is resulting in
communities in one part of the country convicting people in *other*
part of the country for "violating local community standards", for
things like BBSes and web sites. Convicting a couple running a BBS in
California for violating the standards in *Tennessee* (they didn\'t do
*anything* in Tennessee, the folks in Tennesssee had to call *them*,
long distance!) is just one example.

The court wants no part of this either. 

In both cases, ruling *either* way will severely upset *huge* numbers
of people. And forever change a fundamental aspect of American society.

In the former, they will either have to rule that the 2nd says "no law"
and *means* "no law", throwing out thousands of laws across the
country and enraging the anti-gun forces. Or they\'ll have to rule in
some manner that agrees with the really quite severe restrictions many
places place on weapons. And convince all the fringie militia types
that it reaaly *is* time for a revolution, since the Constitution is
being ignored.

Likewise, in the latter cases, it\'s pretty unlikely that they *can*
rule in favor of the current laws. And the current standard pretty much
used up the "wiggle room. If they rule on free speech versus
"obscenity" they have exactly two "viable" options:

1. make a *national* standard and set it to the tastes of the most
   liberal places in the country. 
2. finally discard the whole concept and state that it\'s nobody\'s
   business what an adult reads or watches.

They *can\'t* rule that we are all stuck with the standards of the
*strictest* places in the country. The rest of the country would simply
pass a law stating otherwise. And frankly, the fact that they\'d *had*
to go from a "national standard" to a "local" one way back when shows
that a *strict* national standard won\'t fly. 

But going with 1 or 2 will convince the "moralists" that "Satan has
taken over". And again we\'ll have major sections of the population
ready to revolt.

OBTrav: Does the Imperial government ever run into this sort of
problem. Cases where no matter *how* you interpret the law, large
population segments on a planet will be upset to the point of riot or
revolt? 

