>doesn\'t mean, "the right to bear arms, _that is_, the
>right to form state militias, shall not be infringed"?

Not wanting to get into gun control (OT flamebait). However, historically,
the US was not a gun owning society to any great degree from the end of the
18th century through the first half of the 19th century. Through this
period, private gun ownership was relatively rare, guns in private hands
were generally poorly maintained, the militias were, with minor exception,
a joke, and their was no culture, even in rural areas, that especially
valued guns, with the exception of a handful of hunters and trappers. The
evidence for this includes
two gun ownership surveys performed at the state level and tens of
thousands of wills that either do not list guns (which at the time were
_very_ expensive
relative to income) or list them in damaged condition.

Gun ownership in America took off after the Civil War, when a combination
of industrialization made guns much cheaper, wartime taught millions of
Americans how to shoot, and units permitted firearms to remain in private
hands after the war.  The result was a post-war mainstreaming of rifle and
shotgun ownership.

obTrav:  Any war with a massive civilian call-up in an era where firearms
are both issued and retained by soldiers post-enlistment is likely to have
a huge effect on law levels in the region unless strenous steps are taken
by the government to control arms afterward.  This is especially so for
civil wars.

In Traveller, we have an interesting situation where free traders and other
civilian starships are heavily militarized, with private ownership of very
heavy ordinance.  I suspect that this is a tradition that dates back
directly from militirzation of shipping following the Long Night.







