    'index' => 'eh060',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'Leonard Erickson writes:
In mail you write:
>>From Life, the science of biology (Purves et al, 1992):
>>"Here we discuss pigments that play roles in
>>photosynthesis... Of these, the most important are the
>>chlorophylls." "...all photosynthetic organisms possess
>>accessory pigments that absorb photons intermediate in
>>energy between the red and blue and then transfer a
>>portion of the energy to chlorophyll..."  Interestingly
>>enough, while all known Terran photosynthetic organisms
>>have accessory pigments (such as carotenoids and
>>phycobilins), not all of them have chlorophyll.
>>Photosynthetic halobacteria use a derivative of retinol,
>>called bacteriorhodopsin, rather than chlorophyll.
>Ok, that tells me something I didn\'t know. *But*, it also says
>that they *transfer* the energy to Chlorophyll. My guess would
>be that they act like the phosphors in fluorescent tubes and
>absorb certain wavelengths and re-emit them at others more
>suitable.

	Good guess, but incorrect.  They transfer electrons to the
	chlorophyll.

>So they *aid* photosynthesis, but don\'t do it. The
>bacteriorhodopsin is a different matter.

	You are arguing semantics.  By some definitions, one might
	exclude the activity of bacteriorhodopsin since it doesn\'t
	produce chemical reduction (only ATP), but I have no problem
	with including bacteriorhodopsin and carotenoids as pigments
	involved in photosynthesis.
		My original quote: "Chlorophyll is the most important
		photosynthetic pigment found here on Terra, but there
		are other pigments involved in many species."

>What I meant was that it\'s more important that there be enough
>energy at wavelengths the pigment can use, than what the overal
>frequency composition is, and it\'s *especially* not that important
>where the emission peak is. 
>*Efficiency* at converting available light into sugar is more
>important than sensitivity to specific wavelengths.

	The plant still needs to interact with the light that is
	available on that world.

Peez
