    'date' => 'Wed, 15 Dec 1999 10:43:59  0500 (EST)',
    'id' => undef,
    'ts-index' => '1999-12-15.eh061',
    'body' => '<sniff sniff> What\'s that smell?  Smells like burning gunpowder...Ah!  It
must be time for the annual TML 2nd Amendment Flamefest! :-)

I normally try not to perpetuate OT threads, but I just wanted to point
out that explanations of differences in violence levels between countries
based on differences in cultural mixes don\'t really wash.  Canada is one
of the most ethnically diverse countries in the world and we have fairly
low levels of violence.  This despite cultural differences both overt
(Toronto has large numbers of both black and white people, Vancouver a
similar situation with asian immigrants) and subtle (Montreal has French
and English populations who also differ denominationally).  None of these
groups goes about shooting one another, however. 

One might argue that population density or weather has something to do
with differences in levels of violence, but comparing Toronto to Detroit
puts the lie to this. Both cities have about the same climate (being just
across a straight from one another) and both have roughly the same
population.  Yet Detroit has roughly 10 times the murder rate. 

Something I\'d be interested in knowing, if anyone has the stats, is what
the "gun density" of different countries/cities is, and how this relates
to levels of violence.  I\'m not talking about restrictiveness of gun laws
here, but number of guns per person.  The more common guns are, the more
difficult it becomes for laws to keep them out of the hands of criminals.
Consider for argument\'s sake the case where guns are as common as blades
of grass: no laws could prevent anyone who wanted one from obtaining one. 
I have a feeling this is the problem in the US, though admittedly it\'s
just and intuition... 

Charles C. (whose next post will be on-topic, promise!)
