    'subj' => 'Re: Velocity/Vector',
    'from' => 'Charles Collin charles@hebb.psych.mcgill',
    'body' => 'Just to throw my two cents in here I use a system where emergence from
jump causes one\'s vector direction to be randomized.  This is a
side-effect of the energy put into the jump.  The length of the vector
stays the same relative to the point of jump entry, so it\'s generally in
one\'s best interest to slow down before jumping.  This minimizes the
variability of the time it will take to intercept the world one is headed
to.  The randomization of the vector also attenuates the "near-c" rock
problem, whereby ships which retain their vectors in any predictable way
could jump in on high-speed collision courses with enemy worlds.  

This is my favorite solution as it does little violence to physics and
helps nix near-c rocks. 

Charles C.
