    'ts-index' => '1999-12-15.eh065',
    'body' => 'Leonard Erickson writes:
>I was just trying to make sure that folks understood that
>conserving velocity relative to *different* objects *was*
>"bending physics".
>I can accept people bending or breaking the laws of physics in
>games or stories. But only if they *know* they are breaking
>them, and have thought things thru. Otherwise, the law of
>unintended consequences tends to jump out and bite you. :-)

	I agree, but if you\'re playing Traveller (at least CT), 
	you\'ve already been bit.  :)

>>>Don\'t forget that the time you spend in jump *varies*.
>>That is what most people assume.  I allow some variation,
>>but not anything like a day.
>It\'s in the rules, at least some editions allow for bout that
>much variation.

	I have never seen this in CT (which does not mean that it
	isn\'t there), but I\'ve never worried too much about following
	every rule to the letter.  I don\'t know what rules Josh
	Spencer uses, so I tried to avoid making any assumptions.

>Well, I\'m making the (reasonable, in my opinion) assumption that
>you "aim" your jump for a specific *location*. That is, you in
>effect tell the computer, we want to go *this* distance, in *that*
>direction. And if you don\'t misjump, you exit jump at the target
>point plus/minus a bit for uncontrollable "random" factors.

	Well, I\'m making the (reasonable, in my opinion) assumption
	that you "aim" your jump along a specific jump-space
	trajectory.  That is, you calculate what "direction" you need
	to go in jump-space to get to a given location (given the
	current distribution of masses in real-space) and tell the
	computer (that\'s what the navigator does).  If you don\'t
	missjump, you exit at the target point plus/minus a lot for
	uncontrolled factors.

>This fits in fairly well with Mark Miller\'s statements that if
>your jump "line" intersects the 100 diameter limit of anything
>between your entry to jump and your planned exit, you pop out of
>jump there.

	I am glad that Mr. Miller didn\'t put this in CT (AFAIK), as
	I dislike it.  IMTU, there is nothing between jump entry
	and jump exit, regardless of what may be between the two
	points in real-space.

>He hasn\'t answered my question about *when* you pop out of jump.
>You see, if you work it out, there could be a planet in the way
>for only a few hours. So it matters if those few hours occur when
>the ship is in that part of the jump.
<snipped>

	Sticky problem, I have no useful ideas.  Good luck.

>Whatever way folks decide to handle things, it needs to be
>*logical*. Not merely arbritary decision stacked on top of
>arbtrary decision. That leads you into situations where you
>have to make more and more arbitrary decisions because *previous*
>decision have logical consequences that contradict each other.
<snipped>

	IMHO, the arbitrary decisions have already been made: the
	Traveller rules.  I try to be as logical as I can while
	remaining consistent with my interpretation of those rules
	(and a buch of tweeks).  Fortunately, IMTU, jump physics is
	an area with few consequences for anything other that
	jumping ships (an exception is teleportation, which I regard
	as a form of jump).  This allows me some latitude in setting
	laws that will not mess up the universe much more than it
	already is.

Peez
