In 1995 I was still living in Ohio but was travelling to California for an
anime convention, Anime Expo 95.  That summer was the height of the
Unabomber situation.

I had a large box in my carry-on which had a picture of the contents:  a
Japanese electronic toy which is a plastic globe on a pink pedestal.
Inside the globe, sitting on a plastic throne, is a plastic figure of
Sailor Moon.  When you pass your hand over the top of the globe, Sailor
Moon tells your fortune in Japanese to the accompaniment of music and
flashing lights.  The directions for using the toy were on the outer part
of the box.  In Japanese, of course.

The security personnel were unconvinced that the contents of the box were
a toy even though it was in the original packaging (I was bringing it to a
panel discussion I was part of and the original packaging really is the
best possible protection for it-- it cost me a lot of money to get here in
the US as the shipping was almost as much as the toy) and so they made me
remove it, put in the batteries, and demonstrate it for them.

To the great amusement and irritation of others waiting in line.  Oh, and
Sailor Moon told the big burly security guard that his lucky color was
pink and he was about to meet the most wonderful boy!

