    'month' => '12',
    'topic' => 'RE: Superpowers & Photosynthesis',
    'body' => 'Photosynthesis is a process - and processes involve lots of parts.
Part one is the chlorophyll, which is activated by light to \'catch\'
electrons (simplified, I know). The electrons are then used by enzymes
to convert carbon dioxide and water into sugars. It is possible to use
any source of electrons to run the enzymes - and that is done in
bioreactors. As yet, chlorophyll is the most efficient converter of
sunlight to reductive power (spare electrons) we know of.

