    'body' => '>From: Kyle Schuant <kyle3054@yahoo.com>

>Excuse me, but similarity with small differences 
>causes more violence than _great_ differences. 

Civil wars, insurrections, and rebellions, to relate
to another thread, are traditionally bloodier than
wars between different countries.  

Ob Traveller:  The Civil War period appears to be an
exception to this rule, but it was actually just a
series of naval coups with little public (or
governmental) support or involvement.  On the other
hand, in my Traveller Universe at least, the Fifth
Frontier War is characterized by radical differences
in warfare styles.  

The Imperium on the one hand and the Zhodani and Sword
Worlds on the other fight a relatively conventional
war by: attempting to avoid civilian casualties and
destruction of ecosystems and infrastructures;
treating prisoners with respect and care; and
maintaining communication with each other regarding
prisoners and especially ransom and exchange
negotiations for nobles.

The Vargr forces are primarily in it for the loot, and
everyone recognizes this.  Zhodani advisors try to
keep the Vargr in line with the conventions being used
by the other belligerents, but with limited success. 
The Vargr don\'t hesitate to destroy what they can\'t
take with them, and the Zhodani have to pay them to
leave intact and garrison things that the Zhodani want
(like starports).  

The Vargr don\'t engage in genocide or mass murder of
civilians or prisoners as a matter of general
practice, but they\'re not squeamish about shooting
first and asking questions later, or eliminating
everyone -- civilian or military -- in the way of an
objective.  

An Imperial common citizen would have a hard time
deciding whether it\'s worse to be a Zhodani or Vargr
prisoner.  While the Zhodani might engage in really
disgusting mental practices, the Vargr probably won\'t
provide any medical care and maybe not even food,
unless you convince them that you\'re ransomable.  

The really nasty conflicts involve the Ine Givar, who
will stop at nothing to achieve independence from the
Imperium -- even if it means that Jewell, Regina,
Vilis, and Lanth subsectors become a Zhodani
protectorate.  The Ine Givar\'s primary demands are
total freedom to practice psionics and a restructuring
of the economy to ownership by the state.  

- --Glenn
