> That\'s because NASA designs and runs the damn things like *racecars*.
> Right at the ragged edge of performance. Which is way they have to
> completely disassemble things after each flight. 

Unfortunately, that\'s sort of a prerequisite for getting into orbit.  
> 
> We need something designed like a *truck*, or at least like an
> airplane. Parts and vehicle designed so that the normal flight regime
> is only 50-70 percent of design rating. And designed so they merely
> need regular maintenance.

The problem is, if you have an engine with a specific impulse of 460 seconds, and it takes 730 seconds of thrust to get into orbit plus an additional 120 seconds of thrust to keep from hitting the ground, 14% of your weight can be non-fuel mass.  If you reduce your specific impulse by 10%, only 11% of your weight can be non-fuel mass -- which means your parts need to be 30% stronger, weight for weight, which means that by running one system at _less_ than design rating, other systems need to run at _more_ than design rating.  Getting into space is _hard_.

> I\'m told that due to the influence of th government contractor types
> and NASA the regulations aren\'t real friendly to "small start up"
> companies. 

Maybe.  In practice a small startup is flatly incapable of getting into orbit.  The cheapest way of doing it is buying a missile booster from the USSR, and that\'s still quite expensive.
> 
> > The reasons "private enterprise" hasn\'t gotten into the space game
> > on a free lance basis is that nobody can figure out how to do it
> > less expensively than the "ineficient government bueraucracy."
> 
> Well, I hear that part of the reason for that is that you get required
> to produce tons of paperwork to satisfy government types that you
> aren\'t violating their rules. 

Well, truth is that there are a number of private groups which are doing work on commercial launchers; a number of groups think they _can_ make money at the private launch business, and most likely NASA would be happy to let them do so.

None of this relates to mars exploration, of course.  There\'s no commercial reason to go there.
