    'body' => 'Leonard Erickson <shadow@> wrote:
>Well, I\'m making the (reasonable, in my opinion) assumption that you
>"aim" your jump for a specific *location*. That is, you in effect tell
>the computer, we want to go *this* distance, in *that* direction. And
>if you don\'t misjump, you exit jump at the target point plus/minus a
>bit for uncontrollable "random" factors.
>
>This fits in fairly well with Mark Miller\'s statements that if your
>jump "line" intersects the 100 diameter limit of anything between your
>entry to jump and your planned exit, you pop out of jump there. 
>
>He hasn\'t answered my question about *when* you pop out of jump. You
>see, if you work it out, there could be a planet in the way for only a
>few hours. So it matters if those few hours occur when the ship is in
>that part of the jump. 
>
\'Scuse my de-lurkng for a moment, but has any discussion here covered
the concept of a "ballistic arc" journey through jump space.  This might
help explain the "7 days +/- 1 day" rule if the "up velocity" at start
of jump was constant - or if different jump numbers involved entering
different "jump spaces" each with different "gravity" and "entry/escape
velocity".  Gravity wells in real space warp the real space/jump space
interface in such a scheme so that the jump space side is *smaller*.  A
planet plus its gravity well becomes a very small target when "aiming"
your trajectory through jump space, so you are unlikely to exit jump in
a gravity well.  The dangers of entering jump space while in a gravity
well, OTOH, are pretty evident.  I realise this doesn\'t fit with Marc
Millers T4 pronouncement, but the effect is pretty much the same.

Cheers,

Andy
