    'topic' => 'Subject: Marines & Cutlasses',
    'body' => '>From: "Jim & Peta Lawrie" <jimpeta@primus.com.au>

>    I apologise if this has been raised before but 
>why do Marines get the Cutlass? 

Ah, the annual "use of blade weapons in Traveller"
thrash arrives just as people were starting to tire of
(or really warm up to) the "gun control/U.S.
Constitution" thrash.  No, wait, that isn\'t Jim\'s
question; he accepts blade weapons in the Far Future,
and wants to know, why the cutlass?

>They never used them historically, Marines started 
>out using Muskets and Bayonets and even the officers 
>used a different sword.

Well, what does "historically" mean in our context? 
You are talking about the 1600s to 1800s.  To people
living in the Far Future, that\'s like you and me
discussing what weapons were used by which personnel
on the Pharoah\'s boats.  It has no bearing on
traditions that may only be several hundred years old.

So why the Cutlass, as opposed to the broadsword, dai
katana, kukri, or other blade weapon?  In my Traveller
Universe, the Instellarms LIC engineers who submitted
the winning bid wanted to base the design on an old
Solomani weapon (the Solomani faction being then
ascendant) and thought the cutlass looked the coolest.
 They won the bid (coolness being a factor considered
by Imperial Marine Procurement, but strength,
durability, cost, and other factors also having been
considered) and the rest is history.

>Enlisted Naval personnel were the main users of the 
>Cutlass, they also used Boarding Axes and Boarding 
>Pikes as well all though these don\'t seem to be an 
>option.

Axes are best for breaking through wooden doors and
walls, but there aren\'t many of these aboard
starships; breaching charges are used instead.

Pikes are (1) for grabbing the other ship\'s gunwales
and (2) holding off charging enemy sailor coming over
your gunwales.  There aren\'t any gunwales on
starships, so these don\'t get used in the Far Future.

- --Glenn
