    'index' => 'eh145',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> OB Traveller; Would Belters or have something similar?
>
> "If it\'s stony, extract it"
> "If it\'s ice, melt it"
> "If it\'s carbon, curse it"

Actually, the carbonaceous chodrites are second only to the "ice"
bodies in value. For one thing, "ice" and "CHON" are the *only* sources
of critical life support chemicals like nitrogen in the belt. Ditto for
carbon (for plastics and life support), hydrogen (water and power),
etc. 

Also, in any belt you\'ll have ice *or* chondrites. Ice in the outer
system, where it is cold enough, chondrites in the inner system where
the volatiles got baked out of the ice at the same time UV was
converting surface compounds into complex organics.

So the three types of asteroids are:

1. nickel/iron
2. stony
3. icy *or* chondritic

Nickel/iron is useful for structrul materials, and the "impurities" out
to be fairly useful too (any metals that prefer to go into solution in
iron rather than become part of the "stony" part of a body when a body
differentiates in the early history of a system). Stuff like Iridium,
and other platinum group metals.

I\'ve already covered icy & chondritic bodies.

Which leaves stony bodies. Which are somewhat useful as a source of
oxygen, if you can\'t find anything better. And they\'ve got *lots* of
silicon, aluminum and magnesium. And fair amounts of titanium. So
glass, steel, aluminum, magnesium, and titanium are the major
construction materials in belt habitats. 

Just keep in mind that *all* asteroid "rock" is igneous. No sedimentary
or metamorphic. And it\'s *really* unlikely that there will be any
"hydrothermal" deposits. Thus, no mineral "veins". Just lots and lots
of basalts, granites and the like. (any geologist want to help out
here?) 

So all the stuff we prospect for "ores" of on Earth isn\'t like to
*have* "ores" in the belt. You\'ll just have to extract the silica, then
the alumina, magnesia, and titania (oxides of the relevant elements).
the rest of the stuff will be a mish mash of all *sorts* of stuff. And
seperating it will be a pain.

