    'month' => '12',
    'topic' => ' technology advances',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Leonard Erickson writes:
>> > Space launch vehicles are much more likely to go up in a ball of
>> > vapour if something goes wrong than a 777. Most of the time if something
>> > goes wrong on an airplane you can continue the flight or land at the
>> > nearest airport whereas with a rocket something going wrong is
>> > extremely likely to result in catastrophic failure (ie fireball in the
>> > sky.) 
>> 
>> That\'s because NASA designs and runs the damn things like *racecars*.
>> Right at the ragged edge of performance. Which is way they have to
>> completely disassemble things after each flight. 
>
> Unfortunately, that\'s sort of a prerequisite for getting into orbit.  

Not really. It\'s a requirement for getting the last possible ounce of
payload for a given amount of fuel. But I\'ve read articles by folks
involved with several different "alternative launch systems" that say
much what I did. 

Several designs use deliberately "de-rated (ie operated at well below
the design range) engines specifically to reduce wear and allow longer
operation between *scheduled* maintenance. 

Rocket fuel is *not* the big expense. The fuel required to get you into
orbit might cost as much as a few hundred bucks. Probably a lot less. 

The costs are all expensive parts in the rocket, with their *short*
lifetimes, and the *millions* of man-hours involved in assembling and
maintaining things the NASA way. 
 
>> We need something designed like a *truck*, or at least like an
>> airplane. Parts and vehicle designed so that the normal flight regime
>> is only 50-70 percent of design rating. And designed so they merely
>> need regular maintenance.
>
> The problem is, if you have an engine with a specific impulse of 460
> seconds, and it takes 730 seconds of thrust to get into orbit plus an
> additional 120 seconds of thrust to keep from hitting the ground, 14%
> of your weight can be non-fuel mass.  If you reduce your specific
> impulse by 10%, only 11% of your weight can be non-fuel mass -- which
> means your parts need to be 30% stronger, weight for weight, which
> means that by running one system at _less_ than design rating, other
> systems need to run at _more_  than design rating.  Getting into
> space is _hard_.

This is why multi-stage rockets were invented. They are *not*
inherently "one use". 

Also, just because the parts have to be 30% stronger, that *doesn\'t*
mean that they are running at more than their design rating. 

Please note that the DC-X was designed using "aircraft" design
practices, not "spacecraft" ones. 

>> I\'m told that due to the influence of th government contractor types
>> and NASA the regulations aren\'t real friendly to "small start up"
>> companies. 
>
> Maybe.  In practice a small startup is flatly incapable of getting into 
> orbit.  The cheapest way of doing it is buying a missile booster from the 
> USSR, and that\'s still quite expensive.

You are making unfounded assumptions. A "small startup" won\'t get into
orbit *at first*, anymore than a small startup computer firm will
get picked to be the computer supplier for all the computers in a
Fortune 500 company. 

Startups start out by designing and testing launchers for small
payloads. And for your information, it is possible for "high power"
model rockets to orbit payloads. Nobody has done it yet because not
only is it expensive, but getting the flight plan approved would be a
nightmare. 

Several of the suppliers of the larger model rocket engines have lines
the go from the "model rocket engines" on up to sounding rocket engines
without any sort of a break. Just a steady progression of
impulse/thrust ratings thoroughout the line.

Anyway, a startup either builds around "off the shelf" engines, or they
design their own and buy off the shelf for other things. They do tests
to prove their designs, and as the tests go well they get more
investors and scale things up. Or they fail (either tests or to attract
investors) and they vanish. 

But expecyting them to do the sort of reporting that someone like
Boeing does (where they can afford the staff to file foot thick
reports with the government) is just a bit unreasonable.
 
>> > The reasons "private enterprise" hasn\'t gotten into the space game
>> > on a free lance basis is that nobody can figure out how to do it
>> > less expensively than the "ineficient government bueraucracy."
>> 
>> Well, I hear that part of the reason for that is that you get required
>> to produce tons of paperwork to satisfy government types that you
>> aren\'t violating their rules. 
>
> Well, truth is that there are a number of private groups which are doing 
> work on commercial launchers; a number of groups think they _can_ make money 
> at the private launch business, and most likely NASA would be happy to let 
> them do so.

Depends on who you ask. The rank and file at NASA, sure. Ask the admin
types, they may *say* yes, but their actions say something quite
different. 

