    'body' => '- ---- David Healey <dhealey@giant.net.au> wrote:

> Will some of the more learned members of the list
> correct me if I\'m wrong
> here, buuuut .....
> 
> Wasn\'t the bloodiest hour of combat in history at
> Chancellorsville or was
> it The Seven Days ?  Something like 5000 dead in an
> hour ?  Or is my
> failing memory leading me on ?  IIRC, the bloodiest
> *day* was Day 1 of The
> Somme.

There\'s a lot of competition for the bloodiest day,
week, month and year of war. And then of course it
depends what you call a "war". Some speak of "war
against the people", and in that case China has a
bloody history, with some 30 million killed during the
Cultural Revolution (about ten years), and Stalin came
close in the 30s, with about 25 million killed (at one
point, one in five of the adult male population was in
a labour camp!) However, for myself, I call that plain
old genocide, and "war" means when someone\'s shooting
and someone\'s shooting back (the April Rising in the
Warsaw Ghetto, as opposed to Babi Yar).

Most of the famous battles were bloody ones:
Chansolerville, Antietam, First and Second Bull Run,
Normandy, Monte Cassino, Stalingrad...

And I stick to my contention, the more similar the
nations, the more bloody the conflict. Of course it\'s
true that similar tend to be closer, and therefore
easier to fight with, but that\'s not _always_ the
case. Look at the Hindus and Moslems in
India/Pakistan, for example. Very different religions
and ideas of how to live, yet a long and frequently
bloody conflict.

I guess what I\'m really saying is that neither
difference nor similarity _cause_ conflict (though
similarity makes conflict bloodier, often), but that
something innate in humans causes conflict. We start
the fight, think of an excuse later, all too often.

We see this nowadays. No sooner does the Soviet Union
collapse than we find the West at war with Iraq, and
threatening other such nations like Sudan and North
Korea. Someone once said that once you base your
security on an absolute and ultimate weapon, like the
atom bomb, it becomes psychologically necessary to
believe in an absolute and ultimate enemy.

There are many contenders for Bloodiest Day, but let\'s
face it: armies over the years have killed far more
civilians than soldiers. We don\'t like to focus on it
because it\'s not particularly glorious (like the fact
that most soldiers never shoot at the enemy), and
doesn\'t make for great epic poems and movies. But it\'s
true. 

ObTrav: (this also will be flamebait, I know, but I\'m
just learning the history...) Maybe that\'s why there\'s
so little talk in Trav canon about planet-destroying
weapons (aside from any distaste Miller and his
co-writers may have felt for the topic): the Solomani
have no "ultimate and absolute enemy." They are an
empire without serious challengers.

=====
