    'body' => '> On 12/15/1999 00:46, Bruce Macintosh wrote:
> > 
> > Current tech is straining it a little; Daedalus
> had a
> > laser fusion drive; we can\'t even build a laser
> fusion setup
> > that gets out more energy when its on the ground
> filling
> > several entire buildings.
> > 
> > And Daedalus was automated in spite of a
> hundred-year
> > mission duration; NASA can\'t even build something
> autonamous
> > that can manage to land on Mars...

The Daedalus engine was not going to be a reactor,
which is a reaction that sustains itself without any
energy put in, but a series of explosions, like lots
of little bombs, or, indeed, like a conventional
rocket. We can make an explosion, but not a reactor,
just as the Chinese made fireworks 2000 years before
we were able to make a steam engine. It\'s one thing to
make it go "whoosh!" in a straight line, another to
make something you can turn around, make go faster, go
slower, turn off and start again, store the power
generated, etc...

The automation question is a fair one, the Mars probe
comments likewise. It\'s true  NASA\'s budget has been
cut, and as we\'ve seen in many areas (not least in
British Rail and their recent disaster), cutting
budget means cutting the less glorious parts, like
safety and reliability. But a personal opinion here:
twenty years ago probes were sent out for less money,
and were heaps simpler, and lasted longer than
expected. Voyager 2, Pioneer 11, they\'re still sending
back data, for God\'s sake! And they were only expected
to last until 1982! But the ones we send out now are
much much more complex. 
The moral of the story according to Kyle is: KISS!
(Keep It Simple, Stupid!) My father has an Apple IIc;
it\'s not compatible with today\'s software, but for him
it\'s just a word processor, so it works. He also has a
television he bought in 1978, and that still works
also. Me, I bought a IBM 286, and it self-destructed
before it even had a chance to get obsolete. Ditto
with a Digital television set.
The more complex the system, the more chance it\'ll go
kaput. 
So maybe the petrol tank and old concrete mixer for a
spaceship ain\'t such a bad idea after all...

