    'index' => 'eh193',
    'body' => 'On 12/13/99 at 12:54 PM,  "Eric T. Holmes" <holmberg@thuntek.net> said:

>Fellow Sophonts:

>I have several PCs leaving the ABQ, NM area to go on to RL military
>careers. They have voiced their desire to continue playing using
>e-mail as a means of keeping in contact.  I am looking for ideas on
>how to go about this and have  several questions.  Please answer
>offline, so not to take up TML space unless you feel this a viable
>TML Topic.  I have seen several PBEM Traveller sites and these all
>look cool.  Perhaps you folks with the working experience could
>give some tips.

>1)  Is this an easy task?  

No, it\'s not.  It\'s, at least, as hard a task to keep a PBEM going
as it is to keep a FTF game going.

>2)  How much more time will this require compared to other session
>preparation?

I spend about as much time on game prep for my PBEM as I do for FTF
sessions.  I spend a *lot* of time writing and responding to the
player\'s game posts.  What you do verbally in a 2 hour session can
take 3 or 4 hours in an IRC game and weeks in an email game. 

>3)  How easy are "chat" systems to use during gaming sessions?

I\'ve seen IRC, AOL Messenger, and ICQ all used in online gaming.  I
think, if you can find a small uncrowed ICR server, that\'s the best
method for chat type games.

>4)  How often do you "meet" to play?

For chat type games the norm seems to be once every one to two weeks
for a session.  It\'s best if you can setup a schedule so people can
plan ahead, but like FTF games you can\'t always count on everybody
making to the game.  Do what you\'d do in a FTF game, either ignore
the absent or NPC them.

Email games fall into two different types that I call turn based and
conversational roleplaying.  

Turn based games are where the GM posts the situation and the
players all respond to him with their proposed actions, the GM puts
all the player posts together and responds with what actually
happened, and that starts the cycle again.  One or two "turns" a
week is the best you can really hope for.

Conversational games are more like FTF games where everyone is
gathered around the table talking at once.  The GM posts situations
and NPC actions and words.  The players talk to each other and the
GM\'s NPC\'s, propose actions, and toss both IC (in character) and OOC
(out of character) comments back and forth.  The GM has to
constantly stay involved posting what actually happens as the game
progresses in "real time."  There\'s a lot of "noise" in this method,
but can be a heck of a lot of fun.  For conversational games
everyone posts every day, sometimes several times a day, and still
it can take a month to play out a day. 

>5)  I don\'t have a web site, do I need one?

It\'s not required, but it\'s a *very* good idea.

>6)  If a web site is recommended, where should I go to get the space?

There are lots of choices including, but not limited to, geocities,
xoom, crosswinds, your local isp, and the file space on egroups or
onelist.

>7)  What is the minimum space I can get away with?

If you\'re putting up mostly text, then a couple of meg will do.  If
you are putting up lots of graphics, then you\'ll need lots of space.
You\'ll have to decide what you want to use the site for your game.
 
I don\'t mind lurkers in my PBEM.  If you\'re interested ask me about
it.

Eris

