>
> Actually, there are restrictions in place: Government agencies may ignore
> the FARs, but private corporations may not; if it flys in the US, is not
> owned by a federal government agency, and carries people, it falls under
> the FAA. Anything with an enclosed cockpit needs a type certificate from
> the FAA.

Only for *production* models. Why do you think so many "kit planes" and
homebuilts are registered as "experimental"? The rules are a *lot* looser.

> The FAA doesn\'t issue type certs for rockets, at least according
> to the last set of FAR\'s I have seen (\'92). Once it breaks 28 (IIRC) miles,
> it isn\'t subject to the FAA anymore, but getting to 28 miles without
> violating some FAR is going to be amusing...

And according to the laws Congress passed (enabling legislation)
because of the Space Treaty, the *commerce* department makes the rules
for spacecraft, not the FAA. 

The biggest difference between the "Space Treaty" and the various
international agreements about aviation is one thing. But it makes a
*huge* difference. It was almost certainly included (by the USSR) with
the express intent of making *private* space ventures as hard as
possible.

Under the aviation treaties, while the governments do things like
license and certify operators and vehicles, the liability for anything
that goes wrong rests with the people who did it.

Under the space treaty, the liability rests with the *goverment* of the
people who did it. 

That makes the "proper" laws a bureaucrats dream, and an entrepreneur\'s
nightmare. Because it give the government an *unassailable* reason for
holding veto power over everything you do. 

