>> Actually, there are restrictions in place:
>
> And once there,  you fall under UN rules preventing anyone but a soverign
> nation that is a member of the UN from exploiting any resources.
>
> Does anyone else remember the controversy in the US when your government
> signed that ?

I remember the controversy. I also seem to remember that it was loud
enough that we *didn\'t* sign *that* treaty. 

> There\'s a great little story from (I think) Jerry Pournelle about the first
> commercial exploitation of space being carried out by a group with lots of
> money and power that didn\'t care about breaking the law :.
>
> The Mob.

Heck, dig up a copy of Arthur C. Clarke\'s short "I Remember Babylon".
It has a deal that\'d go over *great* these days. In essence, a DBS
setup (direct broadcast satellite) that, being outside US territory can
ignore US censorship laws. And Saudi laws, and Iranian laws, and...

They don\'t charge for it (after all, scrambling the signal defeats the
purpose). They make their money off of advertising. 

AAnd also, they didn\'t really *care* about making money, since in this
case it was a plot by the KGB to corrupt the US. As they pointed out in
the story, can you just *picture* the US trying to argue *in favor* of
censoring "international broadcasts because the country they are aimed
at doesn\'t approve of the content? Not while Voice of America and Radio
Free Europe still exist! We\'d get laughesd out of whichever forum we
tried the argument in!

And jamming a signal from space isn\'t terribly practical. 

There was a similar story in Analog 10 or 15 years back about "Radio
Free Luna". There were moonbases belonging to various governments, and
some enterprising souls managed to buy, trade for, or salvage enough
gear to build their own habitat. At first they survived by doing "odd
jobs" for the other bases. They they hit on the idea of doing radio
broadcasts to Earth. Stuff like news *without* the spin various
governments give, uncensored records, stuff like that. 

They survived by being scrupulously *neutral, and not *quite* being
annoying enough for the folks on earth to go after them (or the bank
accounts they use to buy supplies with advertising money). The other
folks on the moon *officially* have little to do with them.

Unofficially, nobody on the moon can be bother about that sort of
thing. Kepping things running ok is more important than following the
rules earth sent up about who you can get parts from or who you can
allow to supply labor on jobs. 

I don\'t recall if the story mentions it, but a setup like that on the
moon would have some marked advantages. The antenna is best laid out as
a set of radials, not a tall tower. So that saves on materials *and* is
easier to build. 

The high power stages of the transmitter will (of course) use tubes,
since semiconductors just don\'t handle those power levels. Being in a
fairly decent vacuum, you can just step out side in a suit to build the
power tubes. Build a shack around them, seal it, and pump it out to
required quality of vacuum. It can be pretty flimsy since the
difference between the .001 atm "dirty vacuum" around a base and the
.000001 atm "high quality vacuum" the tubes want isn\'t going to exert
measurable force on the walls. :-)

