    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> On 15 Dec 99, at 15:31, Moody, Danny M. wrote:
>
>> Absolutely untrue!  The Supreme Court itself, many, many times have stated
>> that denying cert means nothing at all - except that they didn\'t want to
>> deal with the issue.
>
> Maybe so, but by not hearing cases dealing with a particular issue, the 
> Supreme Court is allowing whatever it is that is being appealed against 
> to continue.

Well, you have to keep in mind that they *can\'t* hear everything that
gets appealed to them. It\'s simply not possible.

> In the case of gun control by refusing to hear 2nd amendment cases the 
> Supreme Court is allowing state and federal gun control laws to exist 
> and be enforced regardless of thier constitutional legality. 
>
> It strikes me that this is a weakness in the US system - if the Supreme 
> Court won\'t hear cases the constitution can be ignored.

Well, it\'s possible for Congress to write laws with a clause that says
that if there\'s a challenge to the law, it gets "fast tracked" to the
Supreme Court. They did that with the ill-fated Communications Decency
Act a few years back. And the SC basicly told them that they weren\'t
*allowed* to regulate speech that way. So Congress hasn\'t put that
clause in the recent attempt to replace the CDA (which has the exact
same flaws the SC threw out the first one over!). Which means it\'ll
take years of court battles before *it* fets thrown out. 

And then there\'s the case where appeals of different cases involving
the same law lead to different rulings in two different Federal
Circuits (or is it Districts?). Anyway, then the SC has to get
involved. 

Another factor is that if you *win* your case in a lower court, you
can\'t appeal. And the State and Federal prosecutors aren\'t about to
appeal cases that might get laws they want to keep thrown out. 

So just about every time someone can afford the time and legal talent
to challenge many of the gun laws, they win in a lower court, and the
government declines to appeal. Usually, this happens at a low enough
level that it doesn\'t affect the standing of the law outside some very
limited geographical area.

Here\'s an example of the kind of nonsense that\'s gone on. The BATF
(Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms) has to process applications
for the "tax stamp" that is needed to own certain types of weapons. 

At one time, they got the cute idea of stopping all transfers and
purchases of such weapons by declining to accept the forms (or maybe it
was by declining to *print* any). 

This got challenged in court, and made it up pretty far before the
court ruled that if they weren\'t going to allow people to apply for the
stamps, then they couldn\'t then turn around and prosecute people for
not having the stamps!

As I understand it, the feds declined to appeal that to the Supreme
Court (good thing for them, since the SC would have been able to hand
them their heads on a platter *without* having to rule on whether or
not requiring the stamps is a violation of the 2nd amendment). 

The BATF just started processing the paperwork again, rather than risk
what could happen if someone *else* appealed.

