> "sue me, Secretary General. Come and get me!" And moon
> him from orbit.

The way it works is that under that treaty, the asteriod is "common
property of all humanity" or some such. So you could drag it to earth,
refine out the metals, and when you tried to sell them, they\'d just
confiscate them. And thank you for so graciously contributing to the
betterment of humanity.

> As for local laws, I daresay that if some private
> company managed to, say, put a shipload of idiots with
> more money than sense into space, well, they\'d have
> enough money from ticket sales to pay the government
> fines fifty times over.

Not if the government sets the fines at more than they made. Which they
can AND WOULD do. And they\'d throw everyone involved in jail as well. 

Remember, since it is the *government*, not the company, that would
have to pay the damages if that ship knocks out some important
satellites, or crashes and wipes out a good chunk of a city, they are
*not* going to settle for a mere "slap on the wrist" for ignoring their
rules.

Also, due to the way the treaty works, the government could (and likely
*would*) fine the *passengers* as well. Because *they* are guilty of
"conducting space activities" without permission too. 

So the passengers would turn around and sue the company. More likely,
they\'d have been told in advance that they\'d be arrested upon landing
if they took the trip. Which would severely reduce the passenger pool.

