    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> <serious Query, not flamebait>
> Having just rewatched TLC\'s Asteroid Impact, the following occured to me...
>
> Options for a dino-killer type imminent impact:
> Shatter
> Divert
>
> Shattering keeps getting trounced here based upon 100 impacts of 100m is no
> better than 1 impact of 1500m of rock.
>
> Diverting is energy intensive.
>
> Would not shattering, especially at times from impact on the order of 5-10
> weeks, if done with sufficient force, scatter most off a direct impact? And
> if sufficient force is used, would one not be able, especially with
> TTL10-12 capabilites, to deliver sufficient force repeatedly enough to
> reduce the impacts below the atmosphereic deep penetration thresholds?

You have to keep in mind the fact that the gravity well of the planet
acts like a "funnel, and will "focus" the spread out stuff so as to
result in more of it hitting the target than you\'d otherwise think.

Also, depending on the size of the rock, 5-10 weeks out is kinda hard
to pull off. For an object moving at 30 km/sec (earth\'s orbital
velocity) 5 weeks is 90 million km (.6 AU). 10 weeks is 180 million km
(1.2 AU).

That\'s a *long* ways off to detect a body only a few km across. And
since it\'d take weeks (or at least *a* week, if you use jump) to get to
where you can *try* to break it up, you have to detect it even
*farther* away.

Now add in the fact that it\'ll take *weeks* of observation to pin down
the body\'s orbit well enough to determine if it\'ll hit or miss.

This is why Spacewatch *desperately* needs more telescopes and
observing time. So they can locate potential hazards far enough in
advance that something can be done. 
 
