>I did the calculation using RATE with the following:
>New ship cost: 240 Mcr
>Down payment:  48 Mcr
>Loan financed:  192 Mcr
>Monthly payments: 1 Mcr
>
>So, translating that to MSeXcel:
>Nper = 40*12
>Pmt = -1000000
>Pv = 192000000
>Fv = 0
>Type = 1
>Guess = 4%/12
>so the entry was = 12 * RATE(40*12,-1000000,192000000,0,1,4%/12)
>
>I came up with ~ 5.610%, although; when I used the value
>it generated to do a payment schedual, I came up with a
>final balance of $8,381,385.56 after the 480th $1,000,000
>payment.  Who wants a baloon payment of $9,381,385.56?

That\'s because you\'re tripping over the "interest on the interest"
problem.

With your calculation (finding the monthly rate), to convert into an
annual calculation, try this

= ((1+ RATE(40*12 , -1, 192)) ^ 12) - 1

which gives 5.719%

However, if your repayment schedule assumes that at the beginning of
each year, the interest is added to your current debt which is then paid
off at a fixed amount per month, then the rate of 5.522% is correct.

I can\'t remember which is the official definition of APR.
Phil Kitching
