easier.

First, go get FinderPop. The Mac has much more customizable context menus
(like right clicking in Windows), but you have to press the control key
when you click. FinderPop (pintware, send enough to the author to cover
the cost of a pint ;-) has a setting that lets you click and hold, and
then the menu pops up. Still only need one button!

If you get something like a trackball, you can assign the right key the
context menu key combo. But I like FinderPop a LOT, so much so that I find
myself holding the left mouse button down at work, vainly waiting for the
context menu to pop up on my PC.

There\'s a new book out from O\'Reilley, a cross platform Windows <-> Mac
book out it might be worth a browse, of you\'re moving over.

You\'re going to _hate_ that stupid hockey-puck mouse (I know, I\'m a
MacEvangelist, bleed in six colors sort of guy, and _I_ hate that stupid
hockey-puck mouse!) 

Get a MacWarehouse catalog, there\'s a company, I believe it\'s MacAlly,
that makes replacement plastic sides for the puck mouse that turn it into
a more normal mouse shape, for about $9. The part just pop off and on, so
no warrantee problems. Otherwise, so far as I\'ve seen just about any USB
mouse or trackball works, (even if they have PeeCee only drivers, plug \'em
in...the Mac driver generally works), ditto for keyboards.

Final bit of general advice: if in doubt, try dragging the file onto the
application, drag\'n\'drop is a LOT more pervasive in the MacOS than it is
in Windows.

Welcome to the Light Side of the Force ;-)

