    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Via electronic medium on 12/15/99 1:24 PM, shadow@ wrote:
>
>> OBtrav: Let the players learn this the hard way.
>
> Any ideas on guidelines for play? How many rounds in how much time at so and
> so caliber = what percentage chance of boom, how big a boom, effects of
> boom?

No idea regarding how many or how fast. But "How big a boom" and the
effects of a boom are fairly simple. 

You see, what goes wrong is that things heat up. As they do, they
*expand*. The proper functioning of a suppressor requires that the
bullet pass thru a bunch of washers that seperate a series of chambers.
There has to be a fairly close fit (ie not too much of a gap between
the bullet and the washers) or the suppressor doesn\'t suppress the
noise.

Now, heat this assemblage up *and* subjection to all the vibration
inherent in full auto fire. How long before a bullet clips the edge of
a washer? 

When it does, it\'ll get deflected and almost certainly *jam* in the
next washer. Now the next round fires and you\'ve got what is
effectively a *blocked barrel*!

Luckily suppressers operate at lower pressure than the barrel. The
whole idea is for the expanding gases to expand into those chambers, so
that when the bullet clears the suppressor, the pressure is to low to
make a "bang", but instead makes a more subdued "pop". 

But you are still dealing with metal being ripped apart by pressure. 

- -- 
