Leonard (very fairly) asked:
>Got a chapter and verse for that? Or at least a chapter?


Drat!  I knew you\'d ask that.  Fortunately, I work in a Library and after a
bit of a hunt...

2 Samuel 6   (and the same story in 1 Chronicles 13)

the relevant bit is this for those who can\'t be bothered to look it up:

"Once more David called together the best soldiers in Israel, a total of
thirty thousand men, and led them to Baalah in Judah, in order to bring
there God\'s Covenant Box, bearing the name of the Lord Almighty, whose
throne is above the winged creatures.  They took it from Abinadab\'s home on
the hill and placed it on a new cart.  Uzzah and Ahio, sons of Abinadab,
were guiding the cart, with Ahio walking in front.  David and all the
Israelits were dancing and singing with all their might to honour the Lord.
They were playing harps, lyres, drums, rattles, and cymbals.

As they came to the threshing-place of Nacon, the oxen stumbled, and Uzzah
reached out and took hold of the Covenant Box.  At once the Lord God became
angry with Uzzah and killed him because of his irrevrance.  Uzzah died
there beside the Covenant Box, and so that place has been called Perez
Uzzah (Punishment of Uzzah) ever since.  David was furious because the Lord
had punished Uzzah in anger."  (Today\'s English Version - something of a
paraphrase - i.e. \'liberal modern language\' translation).

(It then goes on about David being too scared to move it, it blessing the
home of the guy who stored it for 3 months, and then David - having heard
about the blessing - moving it to Jerusalem.  He dances in front of it
wearing very little and has his wife object to the embarrassment.  The
chapter bluntly finishes: "she never had any children".)

A commentary I found says this:
"The punishment of Uzzah has often been objected to as excessive,
especially as his intention was good.  Addording to the law the ark had to
be treated with very great reverence as a symbol of God\'s presence, e.g.,
not to be touched but carried on staves (Exodus 25:14,15. cf Numbers
4:15,20).  The majesty of the holy One was symbolized by the ark.  It was
necessary to teach the Israelites the infinite holiness of God even if by
\'terrible acts\'.  The ark had been in the house of Abinadab for between 70
and 80 years.  His son Eleazar had been consecrated to care for it (1
Samuel 7:1).  Uzzah and Ahio must have been sons of Abinadab in the wide
sense of \'descendants\' - in this case \'grandsons\'.  Having had the ark so
long in their home they might have been expected to have learned the sacred
regulations concerning it.  The narrative shows, however, that neither
they, nor David, nor his advisers, did so, although the priests and Levites
were concerned in the arrangements (1 Chronicles 13:1-8).  The Levitical
laws laid down that the ark must be carried by the Levites, but they could
not come near it till it was covered by the priests, and they must not
touch it except by staves on pain of death (cf. Numbers 4:5, 15, 19, 20.
See also 1 Chronicles 15:2)."


For further adventures of the Ark (called the Covenant Box in the version I
have to hand) try 1 Samuel 4, 5, 6 and the beginning of 7.  Here you get
all sorts of stuff about the disasters that the Philistines experienced
when they captured the Ark in a battle.


