That is an enjoyable but very dated story.  The KGB,
as I recall, were sending pornographic images --
mostly off Indian temple walls -- set to music.  They
thought people would simply become transfixed to their
televisions and first world productivity would dry up.
 
What must Clarke think if he sees TV today?  You can
see things on prime time that are more explicit than
many Indian temple sculptures, cable channels
broadcast totally hard core pornography, you can find
anything
on the Internet -- and first world productivity is as
high as ever, the economy is booming, military
readiness is high, etc. (and people are transfixed to
their tvs and computers).

(Well, I think Clarke told the story a little
tongue-in-cheek, so he probably doesn\'t think much
about it today.)

Ob Traveller:  This could be a problem on individual
worlds, I suppose, and even between worlds.  "Damn
those Efati, buying our lesser moon and setting up a
transmitter on it, to bombard us with decadent, impure
images.  They are seeking to subvert our culture.  We
won\'t stand for it!  Find me a group of PCs with
demolitions and tactics skill at once!"  

- --Glenn
