I held off making an obscure point during this thread, but since it continued
(and Timothy kindly provided the reference), you make like to note that it
wasn\'t the _inside_ of the Ark that was taboo, but the "mercy seat" (throne) on
top. Inside the box were the 10 Commandments, the rules forming the Israelite
side of the covenant (the contract between God and Israel). On top of the box,
between the two golden angels (cherubim?), was built the "mercy seat". When they
sacrificed animals to cover their sin, the Israelites splashed blood around the
place as purification (church services were a lot messier in those days ;-) and
poured some on the "mercy seat". This was where God\'s presence "rested" when he
came down to talk to Moses. That is why the _outside_ of the box was taboo -
"Raiders" got it wrong in that sense.

However, having Nazis touch the thing at all is probably good enough cause for
the events at the end of the film, anyway.  ;-) ;-)

>The majesty of the holy One was symbolized by the ark.  It was
>necessary to teach the Israelites the infinite holiness of God even if by
>\'terrible acts\'.

