    'from' => 'Kiri Aradia Morgan tiamat@tsoft.com',
    'body' => 'On Thu, 16 Dec 1999, Bruce Johnson wrote:

> Kiri Aradia Morgan wrote:
> > 
> 
> > Actually I\'m a REAL heretic.  One of the culture clashes between the
> > interstellar powers in my universe was that some of the aliens used a warp
> > propulsion for FTL (that the players could never figure out) and others
> > (the ones that the players were from, natch) used Jump.  Made navigation
> > rather harrowing near the borders.  Then there were the Taschiin, a word
> > which means "gods" or "cosmic string-spinning bugs" depending upon whether
> > it is spoken with reverence or contempt...  they don\'t NEED ships.
> > 
> > HERETIC!!!  HERETIC!!!  HERETIC!!!
> > 
> > I know.  Just please don\'t burn me at the stake.
> 
> Naaah, we\'ll just steal your ideas...."cosmic string-spinning bugs..."
> wow, cool concept...mind if I nip off with that one? <snip snip>
> 
So long as I don\'t see it in a novel before I publish mine, feel free to
use it in your game.  I\'m flattered.  I got the idea from reading a bunch
of late 80\'s Thelemic/Voudoun writings about the Haitian Spider Gods that
can go anywhere in space and time by traversing a giant web.  It crossed
my mind that this could be true if the web was made of cosmic string.

The problem was that like the Zariguin I had based them on, a very few
weird Taschiin thought humaniti were interesting.  One thought so enough
to shapeshift itself into a male Talassani form and become the leader of a
cult.  The members of this cult wanted to have his babies, so it
manipulated itself and created something similar enough to human germ
cells that actual pregnancies resulted... and one of the most annoying and
most loved NPC\'s in the storyline was one of the resulting offspring.

"Don\'t get angry with him, Marcus-- he\'s as human as one of your
rosebushes."

"My rosebushes don\'t wander around on their own accord spreading chaos and
meddling in interstellar politics!"

Tisselen had his Lovecraftian moments, but he genuinely meant no harm.  He
just forgot that humans were more fragile than he was and couldn\'t
manipulate atomic forces and things.  He also got attached to several
rather important people, which was a mixed blessing if you were one of
them.

> There\'s a _bunch_ of us heretics about.
> 
> One question...why did the different drives mess with navigation? The
> warp drives dump you out of jump or something?
> 
People using different FTL propulsion systems couldn\'t see each other
coming; when they were not in normal space, they were in different
non-normal spaces.  They might come out in the same place.  And they
couldn\'t always communicate even if their governments were getting along.

Which they often were not.

You could, if you were VERY unlucky, jump into a patch of warped space in
someone else\'s wake.  Or have a starship come out of jump right in front
of your starship.  Not cool.  Led to Philadelphia experiment moments if
you were lucky, which PC ships always were.

This happened very infrequently whether I used CT rules or ST RPG rules
(depending on which side was playing).

"Damn Talassani!"

Kiri  =)
