Ahh, that\'s nothing!  My ethnogenetic background is a mix of
Scotch-Irish, German, and Filipino, giving me olive skin, light brown
eyes, and curly brown hair.  I\'ve had people assume that I speak
Spanish, and other people ask me what my plans were for Passover.  I
have that generic Mediterranean look, I guess, yet none of my known
ancestors are from the Mediterranean region.

Even more amusing was my time in Saudi Arabia during DESERT
SHIELD/DESERT STORM.  As an Arabic linguist, I learned both Syrian and
Egyptian dialects, as well as "Modern Standard" Arabic (MSA).  Nobody in
the Arab world actually _converses_ in MSA, nor do I.  When I arrived in
Saudi Arabia, I consciously avoided speaking in Egyptian dialect, since
Egyptian dialect is largely different from MSA, while Gulf dialect is
much closer to MSA.  As a result, I tended to use Syrian dialect
pronunciations and phrasings.  Bottom line is, most Saudis with whom I
spoke asked me if I was Lebanese.  Between my Syrian/Lebanese accent,
and my Mediterranean appearance, they assumed that, while I was
obviously not a native speaker (in the sense that I do not have
native-level fluency in Arabic), I must have been a second or third
generation Lebanese.

Rather than explain all of the above, I simply told them that, while _I_
was not Lebanese, my teacher was (mostly true, BTW [I had quite a few
teachers at the military language school, some of whom were Lebanese]).

ObTrav:  I\'m given to understand that Solomani are the most physically
diverse race of humaniti.  If this is the case, then I can see cases in
which either ethnic Solomani are mistaken for one of the other races of
humaniti, or members of another race of humaniti are mistaken for
Solomani, based on the combination of appearance and accent when
speaking a given language.

Of course, many Solomani (even Imperial citizens of Solomani ancestry),
if mistaken for a "lesser" branch of humaniti, would likely take
offense.  Much comedy ensues....

