   It should also be pointed out that the initial battle of the American
Revolutionary War (Lexington) occurred because the British Army decided to
seize private citizens\' weapons that were being held in community arsenals
outside of Boston.

   Harold\'s Thoughts On Gun Control (send replies to hdhale@mindspring.com)

   1) While there are similarities between the U.S., Canada, Finland, New
Zealand, Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and France, the U.S. is
culturally different enough from Canada, Finland, New Zealand, Switzerland,
the United Kingdom, and France that gun control debates that resort to
comparing this and that country\'s statistics (especially those that imply
that the U.S. should give up private ownership of guns like a child gives
up its "blankee" or favorite stuffed animal) are nothing more than a
philosophical exercise with little practical value.  If you are lucky
enough to live in the country with a relatively homogenous population that
has a tradition of resolving serious differences over several alcoholic
beverages and a couple of fists or one really serious opium binge, good for
you.  The rest of us will find our own path.

   2) It can be accurately pointed out that governments and peoples have
from time to time in the course of history deemed it appropriate to
concentrate the ability to use force in the form of projectile weapons in
the hands of the state.  When this has happened, the resulting changes in
society have been mixed at best.  Hitler made sure that guns were rounded
up when he took power in the 1930s.  On the other hand the UK rounded up
most all firearms in the 1920s when fear spread of a Communist insurgency.
The former resulted in one of the most repressive regimes in history.  The
latter has been a stable democracy ever since (even if you may disagree
with the policies of the current Labour Government).

   3) A firearm is a weapon capable of killing people with greater
efficiency than with knives, swords, arrows, cars, clubs, ropes, bare
hands, etc.  That\'s *all* a firearm really is--a more efficient machine.
Not as efficient as poison gas, nuclear power, or a 747 perhaps, but on the
scale of things, effective for what it is design to do.  It is incapable of
killing in and of itself unless it is seriously mechanically defective, and
then it does so, it does it completely without malice or forethought, just
like a car with bad brakes on a long hill.  In fact there is nothing
inherently evil in any human-built machine, regardless of its purpose or
how "cold" or "military" it looks.  A firearm is a piece of reasonably well
manufactured metal, plastic, and/or wood or ivory and nothing more than
that until *someone* puts it to use.  Then, it can make save a life or even
countless lives by killing or wounding someone(s) intent on doing harm.  It
can also be used to kill babies, elderly women, pregnant mothers, and
Presidents.  *Why* it is used is what is important, not whether or not it
can hold 10 rounds or 20, whether or not it has a flash supresser, or if it
has a detachable magazine.

   4) Banning firearms will not prevent murder or even mass murder.  The
Oklahoma City bombing was carried out and killed hundreds of people without
a single shot being fired.  The IRA killed and wounded far more people with
bombs in their campaign to drive the British out of Northern Ireland than
they ever did with guns.  The gas attacks on the Tokyo subway system a few
years ago were also conducted without firearms.  Tribesmen in Africa have
conducted killing sprees with machetes that killed and wounded dozens even
hundreds at a time.  The History texts are filled with people who had no
trouble butchering, mutilating, raping, and oppressing their fellow men and
women without so much as a whiff of gunpowder in the air.  Is it possible
that some of those people could have killed many more if they had a
firearm?  Perhaps--then again, maybe some of those who chose to use
firearms to do their deeds would have instead resorted to even more
efficient means of killing such as explosives (mixed in a bath tub out of
common chemicals) or worse if a firearm hadn\'t been there.

   5) The Constitution of the U.S. is quite clear--private citizens are
allowed to own firearms and the central government cannot prevent them from
doing so as long as they abide by the laws of the land.  The U.S.
Constitution also states, quite unambiguously, that the Congress should
provide funding to provide private citizens in the proper military
training, and shall appoint officers as necessary so that the private
citizens have a chain of command to report to while they are training or
when and if they ever get called on to protect the country.  So far as I
know, the Congress hasn\'t appointed a single officer for such a purpose
since the 1800s, and they stopped providing funding for firearms training
(let alone training in proper military drill) years ago.  Technically
speaking, this means that Congress has not lived up to its Constitutional
obligations, and corrective actions should be taken immediately by the
President of the U.S. and/or the people.  But wait, not even President
Ronald Reagan, known 2nd Amendment advocate, believed that Congress should
provide funding for training private citizens for military duty outside the
confines of the U.S. military, and I never heard one peep from him during
the 1980s about appointing officers for that chain of command the
aforementioned private citizens are suppose to have.  If the primary reason
stated for private gun ownership is suppose to be about having a "well
regulated militia" (as the U.S. Constitution states), and the militia is
suppose to consist of eligible members of the aforementioned private
citizenry (excluding the National Guard, which, sorry folks, is a part of
the U.S. Army/Air Force) then the militia has been allowed to fall into
disrepair and needs to be immediately funded, or the Second Amendment
repealed.

   6) On the other hand, the Supreme Court of the U.S. has seen fit to give
the citizens of the U.S. the right to an abortion (Roe vs. Wade) through
intepreting the U.S. Constitution to say that a woman\'s choice to terminate
a pregnancy is protected, even though it is not explicitly stated as such;
that burning an American flag in protect is a form of free speech, though
it is not explicitedly stated; that religious displays can be banned in
certain public areas even though the First Amendment does not explicitly
state this; that separate but equal facilities for minorities are
unconstitutional, even though it is not explicitedly stated.  The point is,
many things have been judged by the Supreme Court as constitutional or
unconstitutional based on far less supporting evidence in the U.S.
Constitution than exists currently for private gun ownership.  One would
think that those who support abortion rights, flag burning, exclusion of
religious symbols, and integration would also support private gun
ownership, but as I have noted on more than one occasion, many Americans
have a rather sad tendency to be total and complete flaming hypocrites when
it comes to their personal behavior and to their supposed beliefs on what
constitutes "inalienable rights".

   One more point: given the large volume of gun laws currently on the
books regarding private firearms ownership in the U.S., it could be argued
that the "militia" (eligible private citizens) are already "well
regulated", and that the provisions for funding the appointment of officers
and training the militia were intended for the purposes of preparing for
repelling a foreign invasion only--the threat of which the U.S. has been
free of since 1815.  Also, if the U.S. Supreme Court has been reluctant in
the past to hear 2nd Amendment cases, it has been because they wished to
give local authorities the maximum flexibility possible in how they wished
to deal with gun laws, not because they were necessarily pro or anti-gun.
Any significant ruling by the Supreme Court would have altered that ability.

   7) People who live in mansions and "gated communities" surrounded by
high walls, steel gates, costly high tech security systems, 24 hours
guards, and access to police who will respond in under 7 minutes to a phone
call (Rosie O\'Donnell, Jane Fonda, Sharon Stone, insert the name of your
favorite rich elitist celebrity here) have no business lecturing *anyone*,
particularly people living in cities where illegal drugs and illegal
weapons follow in and out of neighborhoods like sewage through a sewage
line, about whatever less expensive security measures they may take,
including the ownership of a legally obtained firearm.  Further, they have
no business lecturing people on why further weapons bans should be put in
place, since whatever additional bans in the U.S. they propose will
disproportionately disarm honest citizens, while leaving criminals with the
same steady flow of illegal firearms they had before.

   I think I\'ve covered all the bases now regarding people\'s comments on
gun control during the latest "outbreak".  I will post nothing further here
on this topic unless in the above lecture I have made some sort of factual
error that needs correcting.  Those who wish to discuss this further, the
address is listed above.

Regards,

Harold
