    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'At 01:26 PM 12/17/99 -0500, you wrote:
>Date: Fri, 17 Dec 1999 00:54:02 -0800
>From: Jesse DeGraff <jdegraff@pacbell.net>
>Subject: RE: chicks with guns, and 3I porno

> In the United States, those States and
>Municipalities where concealed carry is on a shall-issue basis have lower
>average crime rates, while neighboring states and municipalities with more
>draconian restrictions have higher crime rates.  More guns = less crime.
>Proven fact.

Sigh. It\'s a ridiculous argument.  All it proves is that gun laws don\'t
work with an open border system, in which case, yes-sir-ree, it\'s better to
mug someone you  know is less likely to be carrying.

I can drive from Vermont to New York without being stopped by customs
officials.  I can have a friend with a Vermont address buy a gun in
Vermont, have him hand it to me outside the store (after any waiting period)
and then drive to New York. If I keep a few km over the speed limit, I\'m
not going to be stopped.  That\'s gun control?

obTrav, it\'s like saying that you have two planets next to each other. One
is Law Level 0 and the other Law Level 10.  But there\'s no border control
and no customs patrol.  Guess what happens?  Right. Anyone willing to break
the law can.

You want gun control, enforce a country-wide set of restrictions, eliminate
all "grandfather clauses" allowing resale of existing weapons et al (use
buy-backs if necessary), enforce drug law level penalties for
non-complience (mandatory sentencing, like there is for crack cocaine) and
offer $5,000 buy-back on any firearm not covered by the licensing. Cost you
a few billion dollars, but if you\'ve the stones for it...

Otherwise, all you can say is "the half-hearted, castrated gun laws that
the United States can pass are ineffective in reducing crime."  Thought
experiment: try it with drugs as well. Ban \'em in one state, allow
relatively free sales in another, and see what happens. Answer: more crime.
 Why?  Smuggling, ease of access, etc.

What the US needs is _one_ system. Either the same lack of gun laws
everywhere, or the same gun control everywhere. Only then can you have a
fair trial of whether "more guns = less crime" is a proven fact or not.
















