> This discussion points out one of the weaker points in "Traveller
> sociology" -- the assumption that the Vilani, Zhodani, etc. all lack the
> genetic, phenotypical, linguistic, and cultural diversity of the Solomani,
> because small numbers were transplanted while the Solomani had a somehow
> fuller gene pool to draw on. This is totally indefensible on a linguistic
> and cultural ground, I\'m willing to fight to the bitter end; on the
> genetic and biological side, I\'ll defer to more versed phys anthro types
> here, but from what I understand there\'s no real support for that either.

The logic goes, I believe, that it wasn\'t just the smaller gene pool,
but the overall small number of inhabitants living in a small geographical
area for the other human races that caused their relative homogenity.

While there were probably a number of languages on early Vland, by the
time they achieved space flight I imagine that they really and truly had
whittled it down to one language. Even then, they were starting with a
smaller set of languages to start with.

I imagine the situation would be like dialects of Chinese more than
wholly different languages - they\'re different, but not as different
as they could be.

That\'s for the Vilani and Zhodani at least - they\'re described that way
in "source". Minor human races may be different.
