>    Are these paid on the same world as the bank which funded the loan is?

        To be frank, I\'ve never worried about it.  <gasp>  Yeah, I know.
Since I drive the internal workings of the TNEC millieu on the gold/
platinum exchange system, really what the ship owner is doing is "buying" an
electronic purchase marker for the equivalent value of bullion, with
instructions to transfer same to the bank extending the loan.

>If your Free Trader is away speculating from the ships/banks homeworld and
>there isn\'t enough money in the bank are you automatically assumed to have
>skipped? 

        Like most modern banks, a simple communique of intentions will keep
the hounds in the kennel.  For instance, my own personal bank will defer one
*month* of payments on all my loans with them once a year, with no penalty
to me (except the accumulation of interest).  Why?  Simple...  its better
for them than having to sell the loan at $0.50/ $1.00 to a collections
company.  All I need to do is call and give them a reasonable reason.
        This is the interesting bit...  IMTU, collections firms exist.  You
skip a couple of payments, and in an area the size of the TNEC millieu, it
doesn\'t take long for that information to get out.  A Collections/
Privateering firm buys the loan from the bank and comes looking for you...
information propogation via couriered data-net means that eventually,
someone will want to collect the KCr100 reward on "information leading to
the aprehension"...  say, the tech who was plugging the fuel lines into your
ship at the starport...
        So, the C&P firm pays MCr18 for the rights to the loan on the
Type-A, MCr1 in rewards to various sources who let them know where to find
the runaways, MCr5 in crew and ship costs for its own personell to find the
skip and pockets the balance of MCr12.5.
        Twelve and a half million in cash is a pretty strong motivator to
find a skipping ship.  It also means that the skipping crew *knows* that
everywhere they go, *someone* will talk, making for an arrow pointing at
them.  They eventually *will* get caught...  unless they flee Known Space
for whatever is beyond the Fringe...

>Can the original loan be used to finance another ship if you want
>to trade up? I\'m glad I always play scouts.

        Again, I use a RealWorld(tm) equity model....  how many payments
have you made, divided by three is the amount of equity in the loan that can
be use to setup the downpayment on the next ship and then you can sell your
existing vessel to pay off the current loan.  As well, tech upgrades,
mid-life refits, and that sort of thing can be paid for by cashing out
whatever equity is in the loan.
        The 100-year-old tramp with a perpetual loan and the finest weapons
and electonics suite in the Terran Sphere isn\'t far-fetched this way...  

