> Around Sacramento (the meth capitol of the world), LSD is usually
>cut with  speed.

I\'m surprised nobody\'s mentioned strychnine yet.

Anyway, there are a few different reasons to cut drugs. It\'s most common
with heroin and cocaine because the purity and quality of those drugs vary
immensely. Some will cut cocaine and heroin to keep the dosages low, and
this can actually be beneficial[1]. In addition, since these drugs are sold
in volume, cutting a drug with another substance can make a supply last
longer. Cocaine is usually much more expensive than methampthetamines, for
example, so cocaine is frequently cut with speed.

On the other hand, some drugs are laced with other drugs on purpose.
Marijuana is frequently laced with PCP, and sometimes crack cocaine. Heroin
and speed are sometimes mixed together as well.

None of these reasons apply to LSD, however. The average dosage of LSD today
is about 90 - 120 *micrograms*. A crystal of concentrated LSD the size of
the tip of a thumb is enough to manufacture many,  many doses. It goes
without saying that acid is not a "volume" drug, and as such there\'s no real
reason to cut acid with anything for economic gain, nor to keep the dosage
low. LSD takes a while to take effect, if you want to rip somebody off, it\'s
cheaper and easier to just sell "blank" pieces of blotter paper. Doses of
LSD are usually eye-dropped onto blotter paper. You would feel nothing if
the same amount of speed, or just about any other drug, was dropped onto the
same blotter paper. Other methods of taking LSD are also physically small.
"Microdots" are just a little bit bigger than the enamel head on an
old-fashioned pin and "geltabs" are a little smaller than a pencil eraser,
and both forms are made up of substances which are far cheaper than anything
anybody would want to cut LSD with.

In the mid-60s, it was common for LSD to be sold in the form of larger
tablets, so it *was* possible, and common, for LSD to be cut and laced with
other drugs for different reasons.

This might be part of the reason why people go on to say that LSD is cut
with other substances. I don\'t think so. Being interested in folklore, which
is why I have the amount of knowledge on the subject that I do, I believe
that there\'s a much simpler explanation:

The onset of an LSD trip, especially when the hit ingested was "dirty"
(either degraded by heat or poorly manufactured) is marked by a tightening
of the muscles (especially in the jaws, back and neck) as well as mild
stomach discomfort. In addition, LSD heightens sensory impressions, so most
people feel a pronounced, but not overly unpleasant soreness or at the base
of their back. The length of time
that it takes for a hit to take effect is between about a half hour and an
hour or so, so people who have taken acid are usually very anxious for any
number of reasons.

The effects of speed are somewhat similar, but considerably more pronounced,
so many people somewhat naturally assume that LSD is cut with speed.
Strychnine is thought to cause similar symptoms, so that substance is
commonly thought to be a culprit as well.

Anyone who has even a little knowledge of the drug and the dosages involved
(and such people are vanishingly rare among acid users) will quickly realize
that cutting LSD with anything makes no sense, and even if it was cut, the
dosage of the other drug would not be nearly that pronounced. In response,
in the acid renaissance of the late 80s and early 90s, there arose the
notion that acid must be cut with a small amount of speed or strychnine to
make it "stick" to the blotter paper. That\'s bunk, though, since blotter
paper will absorb LSD when it is mixed with none other than common, everyday
water.

