    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> one crazy with conventional weapons.  Just like one crazy with an assault
> rifle can killl 10-15 people in two seconds (ifiring into a tighltly packed
> crowd), whereas a guy with a knife would be lucky to manage one.

1. an "assualt rifle" is a *fully automatic* weapon. As such it is
   covered by the laws regarding "machine guns". And only *one* such
   weapon is on record as having been both legally possessed *and* used
   in a crime.
2. The so-called "assualt weapon" (an invention of the media) is a
   *semi-automatic* weapon (one trigger pull, one shot fired). And it
   is *functionally* no different than the majority of hunting rifles.
   The term is applied to weapons that "look military" but are
   otherwise unremarkable. They most certainly are no more dangerous
   than "normal" rifles. Unless you know of someone adding a bayonet
   and *stabbing* people with it?
3. You *cannot* shoot "10-15 people in two seconds" with a semi-auto
   rifle. The mechanism won\'t *operate* that fast. Hell, you can\'t do
   that with most *full* auto weapons. You are describing a "cyclic
   rate" of 300-450 rounds per minute. 
   Next, we come to the *fact* that you can\'t *aim* that fast. If you
   just "spray and pray" you aren\'t likely to *hit* with even half of
   your shots, crowd or no. And you *certainly* won\'t be *killing*
   everyone you hit. That takes either extreme luck or a *properly
   placed* shot. And you aren\'t going to be able to "properly place"
   shots at the rate you claim.
   Please note that the spress with high *death* rates are the ones
   where the perpetrator(s) wandered around *taking their time* aiming
   and shooting. Not the cases where bullets were fired wildly. 
4. *10* shots is standard magazine capacity. 5, if you are using the
    magazines required by many states hunting laws. Yes, if you haver
    an extended magazine, you can have 30 rounds. Which if your rate of
    fire was correct would result in emptying the magazine in *four
    seconds*. As I noted, it reality it\'d take longer. Please note that
    in several of these "shooting sprees" people have tackled the
    gunman when he changed magazines (actually, in the "local" one,
    they tackled him while he still had ammo). *Unlike* a knife, you
    are *safe* once you get close to a man with a rifle. You have to be
    out *beyond* the end of the barrel for him to shoot you. With a
    knife you have to be able to immobilize his hand.

In short, you overestimate both the deadliness and the rate of fire of
weapons. And you grossly *underestimate both the *ease* of tackling
someone with a gun (the folks that have tried mostly didn\'t even get
wounded!) and the *difficulty* of doing so to a man with a knife (or a
machete). I mention the machete because such have been used in recent
years in a couple of killing sprees.

