    'ts-index' => '1999-12-17.eh535',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Moving Gun Control Flamebait away from Trav (like it was on topic), I
> thought I\'d mention the reason I was interested -- I\'ve just finished
> co-authoring HOT RODS AND GUN BUNNIES for Guardians of Order.  It\'s our Big
> Eyes, Small Mouth anime-style guns-and-cars book.  There\'s lots of simple
> rules for guns, but also a lengthy appendix detailing U.S., Canadian and
> Japanese gun laws, and so on.  After having spent a few weeks reading
> the mish-mash of laws in the United States and the sheer illogic of many of
> them (the way AP handgun rounds have been extended to rifle ammo by BATF,
> etc.)

That last came about because politicians just can\'t seem to grasp the
concept that Kevlar vests are *not* "bullet-proof". They are *only*
intended to protect against *typical* PISTOL rounds, which tend to be
low-power, low-velocity. They were *never* intended to protect against
rifle rounds, which, with the exception of the various .22 rounds, are
*high* velocity, *high* power. 

So, not understanding this, they decided to try defining "Armor
Piercing" rounds as those which pentrate a typical "bullet-proof" vest,
rather than as rounds which can penetrate *real* armor.

It doesn\'t help that the cheapest ammo for several types of rifles is
surplus Russian and Soviet military ammo, a lot of which *is* "armor
piercing" in that it contains a steel "penetrator" inside the lead
bullet. Which is moderately irrelevant, since even without the
penetrator, a round would go thru a vest *or* the door of a vehicle.
With the penetrator, it may damage a car engine. 

But the point is that there\'s a difference between "armor piercing" and
"dangerous to cops". Basicly, any round useful for hunting is
"dangerous to cops". 

> I must say I am sympathetic with some of the complaints of gun
> owners... Of course, the Japanese gun laws are rather interesting in
> themselves. "In ALL OF JAPAN only 50 pistol holders licenses will be issued
> at any one time. To get one, shoot expert in an air pistol tournment. Then
> we\'ll do a background check on you _and_ your family. Carry the pistol only
> in a locked box.  And when your pistol isn\'t in use for target practice,
> keep it as the police station." That\'s gun control ):  Of course, a few
> thousand illegal handguns still leak into Japan each year...

And then there\'s those *ultra*-realistic reproduction guns that I hear
are so popular in Japan. Which *used* to be able to interchange parts
with the real thing until there were some unfortunate incidents where
people swapped in a *real* barrel and receiver and shot someone. :-(

- -- 
Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
