    'month' => '12',
    'topic' => ' OT: Hot Rods and Gun Bunnies',
    'body' => 'On 17 Dec 99, at 19:48, Leonard Erickson wrote:

> It doesn\'t help that the cheapest ammo for several types of rifles is
> surplus Russian and Soviet military ammo, a lot of which *is* "armor
> piercing" in that it contains a steel "penetrator" inside the lead bullet.
> Which is moderately irrelevant, since even without the penetrator, a round
> would go thru a vest *or* the door of a vehicle. With the penetrator, it
> may damage a car engine. 

Those soviet or chinese "AP" rounds actually aren\'t really armour 
piercing, and IMO were never meant to be. There "penetrator" is made of 
soft steel and isn\'t really shaped right. Beside given the low 
(relatively speaking) power of the 7.62x39 round they don\'t penetrate 
very well anyway. A friend and I once set up a 1/4" steel plate at 15 
yards from us and shot it up with every weapon we had available. 30-06, 
7.62 NATO, .303 and 7.62x39 ball all penetrated, but the 7.62x39 was 
marginal (obften only partially penetrating). 5.56 NATO would only 
penetrate when it hit an already weakend point (so much for T2K\'s 
penetration ratings). .270 Winchester, 30-06, 7.62 NATO, .303 and .243 
Winchester using soft nosed hunting bullets all penetrated (though the 
.243 was marginal). 12 gauge 1oz shotgun slugs made big dents 1/2 - 
3/4" deep, but didn\'t penetrate, as did 0.58 Minie bullets from a 
Zouave replica (using standard amounts of powder for the original - not 
very hot by today\'s standards). .45 lead ball from my black powder 
rifle made dents with light loads, and would nearly penetrate at 
maximum loading.

We also had some fun shooting at a sloped 1.5" plate that my father 
uses as a backstop on his 100 yards range with various rifles. Judging 
by the size of the craters by 100 yds the 7.62x39 was starting to loose 
some energy, as were the black powder rifles, but the others were still 
blasting along quite nicely. From what I saw you\'d have to be a fair 
way away or wearing a lot of armour before the difference between the 
penetration of ball and a hunting bullet would be significant. What\'s 
more unless your armour was rigid the lack of penetration by shotgun 
slugs and large black powder weapons might not matter very much - I\'d 
say that broken ribs would be the least serious result.

BTW if anyone wants to repeat this experiment mear heavy clothing and 
good saftey glasses. The shotgun slugs, in particular, tend to splash 
and the steel core from 7.62x39 rounds sometimes bouce back if they 
don\'t penetrate.



