    'body' => 'From: Rupert Boleyn <rboleyn@paradise.net.nz>


> However LSD requires a lot more care and skill to make than meth.
>Here  in NZ, from what I\'ve been told, most of the acid is laced with
>speed. Bear in mind that just because there\'s only a few micrograms
>of acid  there\'s no reason that 20 - 40 odd milligrams of speed can\'t
>be added.

Yes, actually there is a really good reason that 20 - 40 odd milligrams of
speed can\'t be added. LSD is most frequently (and I mean most frequently)
sold on "tabs" of blotter paper, the average size of each individual hit is
maybe 4mm x 4mm or 5mm x 5mm and probably weighs in at about 2 milligrams.
That much speed just doesn\'t fit, and to borrow a phrase from an
over-publicized trial: "If it doesn\'t fit, you must acquit!"

Of course, if LSD is sold in some other form, perhaps it\'s possible.

It doesn\'t surprise me that you\'ve been told that it is laced with speed,
though. Anywhere you go in the U.S. you will be told that LSD is laced with
either speed or strychnine. In the U.S. there are now and have been various
organizations which test street drugs, usually affiliated with hospitals and
the like. Even in the early 70s, before LSD made the leap to blotter paper,
strychnine and methamphetamine adulteration were both extremely low,
generally under five percent. I can\'t site a physical source at the moment,
as it\'s been nearly a decade since I did the research. The company PharmChem
used to test street drugs routinely, Dr. Alexander Shulgin, was (or is) the
toxicologist over at the University of California in Berkeley and, IIRC, his
work may be useful if you\'re interested in researching as he\'s done a lot of
work concerning LSD, impurities and adulterants.

[Incidentally, I just checked the DEA\'s website to see if I could get a
quick reference, and there was no mention of the practice of LSD being cut
with other drugs. Make of that what you will, but if the practice was
common, I think that they might mention it, even in passing. They *did*
mention the practice of applying LSD to other substances and pawning them
off as something else which has a higher street value, but that\'s simply a
case of misrepresentation, not a case of LSD being cut with another
substance.]
