Well, if the weapon _has_ an ejection port (for misfires, I guess, if
the weapon uses caseless ammo), then I would think that one could design
the stock with ejection ports on both sides.  Provide a couple of parts
to deflect the brass (if non-caseless) and/or non-firing rounds to the
side away from the firer\'s face, through the port in the appropriate
side of the stock, and you\'re in business.

ISTR that the Steyr AUG bullpup rifle (fires 5.56mm NATO ammunition,
IIRC) is easily converted from right-handed to left-handed firing.

Having been trained on the M16A1, I simply taught myself to fire
right-handed.  After all, while the US Army provided plastic brass
deflectors that clip onto the M16A1, I figured that, in combat, I might
not have a brass deflector handy.
> 
> Ob Trav: I assume everything is ambi, or gene therapy has eliminated left
> hand dominance (sounds very Solomani, doesn\'t it...:-) )

Probably the former; it\'s quite possible that left-hand dominance is a
trait linked to some desirable trait, and that eliminating left-hand
dominance would also eliminate the desirable trait.  Besides, I would
think it unwise to remove _any_ trait from the gene pool, unless it can
be shown that the trait is both uniformly harmful, and has no
counterbalancing benefits.  F\'r instance, while sickle-cell anemia
(having two recessive sickle-cell genes) is harmful, sickle-cell _trait_
(having only one sickle-cell gene) provides resistance to malaria.  The
most likely course would be to discourage two recessive gene carriers
from having children that would inherit the harmful recessive gene from
both parents.  How this would be achieved would depend on the
technological prowess and cultural values of the society in question. 
(In other words, with one OT flamewar already raging on the list, I
choose not to kindle another one.)

