If the "Single Payer System" isn\'t a form of socialized medicine, nothing
except the US PHS and similar would be. Looking at the socialized medicine
in the US, it is often payments set at specified rate, and the doctor may
as well be on government wage... and, at least in Alaska\'s Mental Health
Care System, the payment rate is low enough that most private practitioners
won\'t take the cases... Fromm what I\'ve read, canada\'s system is somewhat
better... but, like other forms of limited socialization of a field, prices
tend to be at or near the "approved rates".

I know that my office\'s rates for clients are set to the State Subsidy
levels... basically, since we can\'t charge more than Medicaid and Medicare
will pay, and we aren\'t allowed to have different pricing for non-medicare,
except on a case by case, income-based sliding scale, most private carriers
set payment rates for Mental Health to the Medicaid/Medicare levels... so
all our client time is billed at the subsidy rate, OR LESS...

Ob Trav: I can think of only a few fields that would have subsidies in the
3I: Shipping, Ships, and System Forces. Maybe commo and starports... IMTU,
the "standard Rates" are the 3I\'s voucher redemption rates for 3I personell
and equipment travelling.

