Actually, it is not to laugh, it is to wait...and wait...and wait...

Besides, I forgot....The SE does have a 68000 chip, running at a whopping
16 mhz! (My old Plus runs at 8)

A while back, the MB died on my PPC, and while I was waiting for a
replacment to arrive, I drug out the ol\' Mac Plus to at least dial in for
e-mail...

Whew! \'Twas an...interesting experience, to say the least. I went from a
75 mhz 32bit processor, 96 mb RAM,  2 17" monitors at 24 bit color to a 9\'
B&W screen on a machine with a 40 megabyte HD and 4 Mb of RAM.

It felt like I was working in a shoebox.

But once I swung back into it a while, it wasn\'t nearly as sluggish as I
would have thought. Pretty amazing for an antique...

And the speed difference wasn\'t as apparent as when I went to my (now) 233
mhz 604 from the 75 mhz 601.

Then again, At work I have a 350 mhz PIII that I can\'t really tell a lot
of difference from the 266 PII it used to be. We refresh the technology at
work a _little_ faster than I do at home ;-)

obTrav...what would it be like for someone used to working on TL-14 ships
to sit down at a TL9 console? I mean, the equivalent leap to us is the
difference between a 777 cockpit and a steam locomotive...

