    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Ob Trav: would the Koran, Torah and King James Bible be recognizable in 5700 
> AD?

The Koran will almost certainly be recognizable, and in fact,
unchanged. Mohammed had seen the strife that differing interpretations
and translations caused in the Christian world. So the Koran isn\'t
"supposed" to be translated.

In actuality, it does get translated to allow for more converts. But
the translations are not considered the "real" Koran. Instead, if
there\'s a question about what a passage means, you have to examine the
original Arabic text (which is unchanged and likely to remain so). This
also keeps Arabic alive as a language. 

The Torah is unlikely to change, for similar reasons. The
*commentaries* are likely to be more extensive, but it\'s doubtful that
the actual Torah would change. 

The KJV Bible *can\'t* change, because "KJV" refers to a *specific*
edition/translation. But there are *lots* of translations of the Bible.
And they are rather more likely to *converge than diverge, barring new
archeological discoveries. 

On the other hand:

The interpretations of the Bible will continue to diverge. Islam may
acquire a few more branches. Judaism probably won\'t. And both
Christianity and Islam will generate *more* "daughter religions". 

Examples of "daughter" religions:

Judaism -> Christianity, Islam
Christianity -> Islam, "Mormons"
Islam -> Ba\'hai(sp?)

