    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> My take on races, and please, someone who is knowledgeable in genetics
> please correct me if I am wrong, is that there is only one human race and
> that the various branches of it are merely human adaptations to climate.

Yes and no. Some "racial characteristics" are just plain "random
changes" that spread through a population because they didn\'t *hurt*
anything. 

> Ergo, it follows that if MY ancestors were born in Africa, I too would be
> black and not white as I am today.  I also think that in a few millennia,
> the people who are black and always living in the northern, colder climates,
> will eventually breed light-skinned people, unless they keep re-infusing
> their gene pools from other blacks migrating north.

It\'ll take more than a "few millenia". Remember, what matters is the
number of *generations*. 4000 years is *only* 160 generations. Since we
are *not* deliberately breeding for characteristics, it\'ll take
*thousands* of generations to see noticable changes. Say 25k years
*minimum*.

Then consider that since we developed technology, we tend to adapt
environments to us, instead of the other way around. That *greatly*
reduces selection pressure.

> In essence, to my way of thinking, this invalidates \'racism\' and \'hate
> crimes\' attached to it because we are all one human race.

One species yes. Possibly multiple races.

One interesting possibility is that some of the races of humaniti in
the imperium have "drifted" far enough that they are incapable of
producing fertile offspring with some other races. 

So, say for example, Solomani and Vilani can produce viable offspring,
and Zhodani and Vilani can also, but Solomani and Zhodani *can\'t*. 

That would be *definite* proff that we are dealing with one species,
but different races (sub-species), and also that we are approaching the
point of speciation, if the populations remain (essentially) isolated
for some more generations (lots more).

