Assuming you "borrow" a few famous planets from well known SF:

Mesklin: Since personal computers got powerful enough, Hal Clement was
         able to simulate it himself, and found that the planet is
         *not* an oblate spheriod. It\'s closer to a discus shape(!).
         And while the equatorial gravity remain 3g, polar gravity
         drops to a "mere" 250g.  And the rotational period ("day")
         remains at 17.8 minutes.

I advise caution in adding this planet to your universe. While the
natives are low TL when first contacted, they learn well. And do you
*really* want whatever power "owns" Mesklin to be able to field fighter
pilots who think 250g is "a bit heavy".  

The one bright spot is that Mesklinite reaction times are *not*
superhuman. Just their g-tolerance.

Rocheworld: The most spectacular known "double planet". Two earth-sized
            worlds of almost equal size/mass revolving about a common
            center, just barely outside each other\'s Roche limit. They
            are so close that they shar a common atmosphere. And once a
            year, there is a "waterfall" from one to the other.

Anybody else have some planets that are interesting as *planets*?

Note: don\'t bother trying to use Alan Dean Foster\'s "Moth". Planetary
ring systems can do a lot of neat things, but not *that*!

