    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'eh651',
    'body' => '> ObTrav ... what if the first translation of the Warrant of
> Restoration into planet A\'s native language was mistranslated ... and
> the Imperium liked the mistranslation better, so they never corrected
> it. How would planet A react when they discover they\'re getting
> screwed (more than other worlds)?

There is a real life parallel to this concept which you can use as a
resource for such a background.

In New Zealand, we have a document known as the "Waitangi Treaty", in which
the signatories, who were the "chiefs" of the various Maori tribes
relinquished their sovereignity to the British Crown in exchange for certain
guarantees.

This has two versions, the Maori version and the English version.

To be charitable, it is "unclear" if the differences in meaning were
intentional or just mistranslation, but it has been a bone of contention
ever since.

There are other discrepancies, such as people signing for tribes who may not
have had the right to sign for that tribe, and some tribes who are not
represented at all in the document , and therefore, theoretically have never
relinquished soveriegnity.

When you take into account the abuses of the treaty over the years (on both
sides) there are far more interesting events than I have time to recount
here.

The one thintg I would say is that the Treaty was pushed through by the then
Governor (actually he nmay not have had the title "Governor" at that time)
in an attempt to put in place a legal framework that would give him an
excuse to control the abuses of the _settlers_ (such as the two brothers who
had just "purchased" almost a quarter of the country from a representative
of one of the tribes.) not as the result of a military campaign on either
side.

One of the problems was that there were settlers from many different races
in New Zealand, not all of whom recognzed the right of the British to govern
here, but once the Treaty had been signed, there was "evidence" of the
British Crown controlling the country, allowing the governor to act against
foreign nationals using British law.

In fact, the "Maori Wars", occurred after the treaty.

But we won\'t go into that, I have a major disagreement with the country\'s
"top" historian on that subject, one James Belich, largely because he
obviously knows nothing of military history, claiming the Maori invented
"trench warfare" and similar stupidities.

Frankie




