    'body' => 'Jory Earl writes:
>My take on races, and please, someone who is knowledgeable in
>genetics please correct me if I am wrong, is that there is
>only one human race and that the various branches of it are
>merely human adaptations to climate.

	The distinction between "race" and "species" should be
	defined.  Biologists tend to define species of mammals
	(like us) by whether or not members can successfully
	interbreed.  Thus, horses and donkeys are different
	species because their hybrid (mule) is sterile, and all
	humans are members of same species.  There are problems
	with this definition, but it works well for most mammals.
	A race is somewhat less well defined, but is is similar
	to what biologists call a subspecies (though I would
	avoid that term in PC circles).  A race may be defined
	as a population within a species that are more likely to
	share certain traits with each other than they are with
	members of other races within the same species.  By
	these definitions, we can say that there are different
	races of humans.  The differences between these races are
	though to be, as you suggest, largely due to adaptation
	to local environments.

>Ergo, it follows that if MY ancestors were born in Africa, I too
>would be black and not white as I am today.

	If you go back far enough, your ancestors were born in
	Africa, as far as we know.  :)

>I also think that in a few millennia, the people who are black
>and always living in the northern, colder climates, will
>eventually breed light-skinned people, unless they keep re-
>infusing their gene pools from other blacks migrating north.

	Only if black people in northern climes are less likely
	to reproduce.  Currently, this does not seem to be the
	case, so I wouldn\'t expect the dark skin pigment in these
	families to disappear.

>In essence, to my way of thinking, this invalidates \'racism\'
>and \'hate crimes\' attached to it because we are all one human
>race.

	You are correct, I am only fine-tuning the terminology
	and throwing some light on the evolutionary process.
	There is absolutely no support for racism in evolutionary
	biology, although some have tried to twist the science to
	their own ends.

