    'body' => '	I\'ve seen this notion of the US and Canada pop up in a number of
SF futures.  Shadowrun for one had some of the central eastern states and
provinces join together.  Personally I seriously doubt that Canada would
voluntarily choose to join with the US.  Despite issues about "national
identity crises" and so on, we\'re generally quite proud of our vast
wasteland (and hey, we\'ve been #1 on the UN\'s list of "countries that are
good to live in" for what, four years in a row now? :-). 

	As for military take-over, I sometimes wonder why it hasn\'t
happened yet.  No offence to our army men (both of you) but it would be
something of a cake-walk for the U.S. to take over Canada.  Apparently
plans have been drawn up on both sides of the border for just such an
eventuality.  The Canadian side would be trying a retreating defense and
guerilla tactics until (hopefully) someone else came to help us.  At the
moment, there is no political or economic incentive for the US to do this,
of course, but at times in the past there has been sufficient tension. 
Luckily Britain was a bigger power at the time and was protecting us.  Do
I remeber correctly that there is an American founding document (I don\'t
think the constitution itself, but soemthing related) that specifically
allows for Canadian provinces to becomes states? 

	Another possibility which has been mentioned is the seperation of
Quebec leading the maritimes to joine the US.  I really don\'t see why this
would be the case.  Alaska is physically seperate from the 48 continental
states, but it doesn\'t get any sudden urges to join Canada or Russia.
Presumably post-seperation relations between Canada and Quebec would be
reasonably peaceful (though tense), allowing Canadian cargoes through and
so on. Given that Quebec would seek to join NAFTA (it would have to, to
avoid even worse economic consequences than would already arise from
seperation)  flow of goods and political power to the maritimes should be
pretty smooth.

	The most likely scenario I see, given the present trend towards
everyone wanting their own individual state ("The Republic of Bob", "The
Republic of Tracy"...), is a fragmentation of Canada and perhaps the US as
well into a number of independent states within a free-trade zone.  I
could see a seperate Quebec, perhaps a seperate B.C/Alberta and maybe a
seperate Texas (Not sure about the modern realism of the last, but it has
been the case before, correct?).  Not that I want any of this, I think
Quebec would be economically shooting itself in the foot (or maybe the
head) by seperating.

Oops, this has gotten to be a lengthy off-topic post.  Focus! Focus!

Charles C.
