    'body' => 'On Sat, 18 Dec 1999 20:01:17 -0500 (EST), "Chris Seamans"
<semo@pil.net> wrote:

>From: David J. Golden <goldendj@pcisys.net>

>> Interesting ... never heard this one. Any reason it hasn\'t been
>> corrected in any of the umpteen updated and redone translations
>>since KJ? My copy of the NRSV still has it steal/covet ...

>My own bet is that it\'s not a *complete* mistranslation, probably more along
>the lines that the words in the original text are such that an ambiguity in
>translation is possible. I remember reading that one of the terms for God in
>the Old Testament can be translated as singular or plural, for example,
>which has caused some people to say that a single God is a mistranslation.

>I don\'t know enough beyond that to chime in.

You\'re pretty close - Hebrew and Aramaic were generally not (and
still generally are not) written with vowels indicated.  Instead,
words were indicated with a series of consonants carrying a
specified general meaning, and context was supposed to establish
which vowels - and therefore which specific meaning - actually
occurred.  For example, KTB is the root pertaining to writing;
specifics are KaTaB, the verb "to write", KoTa~B, "writer",
K\'TyBaH, "writing" (as in "thing written"), and so on.  Now,
"witch" is MK.S., which is also the root for "magician",
"tool/instrument", and "stumbling block" in my bad bilingual
Hebrew dictionary - and I don\'t know what else would turn up in a
good one, though I would not find it surprising for "poison" to
be among them. ("Suffer not a stumbling block to live"?  Sounds
good to me; it gives me an excuse to go postal on some of the
turds that work at MISD...)

Incidentally, the specific example you gave, about the word for
G-d being either singular or plural, is also correct; the word
"Elohim" is grammatically male-plural - but I believe that the
singular form, "Elohay" is female.  So add _that_ to the
"confusion"!

