    'index' => 'eh726',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => '>	As for military take-over, I sometimes wonder why it hasn\'t
>happened yet.  No offence to our army men (both of you) but it would be
>something of a cake-walk for the U.S. to take over Canada.  Apparently
>plans have been drawn up on both sides of the border for just such an
>eventuality.

Take a look at the first third of Richard Rohmer\'s novel "Exxoneration"
for the enactment of such a scenario. While I tend to find Rohmer\'s
political viewpoint a little extreme, and the second two-thirds of this
book (the follow-up to another book, "Ultimatum") to be hilariously
unrealistic (PetroCan buys Exxon while Canada joins OPEC? Yeah, right...),
the first third is a fun read.


>	Another possibility which has been mentioned is the seperation of
>Quebec leading the maritimes to joine the US.  I really don\'t see why this
>would be the case.  Alaska is physically seperate from the 48 continental
>states, but it doesn\'t get any sudden urges to join Canada or Russia.

Alaska also has an important resource that allows a certain amount of
self-sufficienty: oil reserves. The Maritime provinces, on the other hand,
are a financial drain on the rest of the country.

>Presumably post-seperation relations between Canada and Quebec would be
>reasonably peaceful (though tense), allowing Canadian cargoes through and
>so on.

The minute Quebec does anything to disrupt the flow of traffic on the
Seaway (which, by treaty, is an international waterway), the US military
will step in to put a stop to it.

>Not that I want any of this, I think
>Quebec would be economically shooting itself in the foot (or maybe the
>head) by seperating.

Still, once Quebec is gone, the government can\'t use the "national unity
crisis" as an excuse to put more important issues (high taxes, the economy)
on the back burner.

>	The most likely scenario I see, given the present trend towards
>everyone wanting their own individual state ("The Republic of Bob", "The
>Republic of Tracy"...), is a fragmentation of Canada and perhaps the US as
>well into a number of independent states within a free-trade zone.  I

Ever read Neal Stephenson\'s novel Snow Crash? The ultimate in a balkanized
United States is depicted therein.


