semester crazies.  Herewith find mine :^)

Personal:  Steve Noe, married over 25 years, 2 daughters, one entering
college next year.  Currently teaching human anatomy and physiology to
allied-health wannabes at Ivy Tech State College in Indianapolis.  I\'ve
run general merchandise stores (anyone old enough to remember WT
Grant?), done research in diagnostic imaging, and done FDA compliance
for medical device and bulk pharmaceutical firms.

Other hobbies:  historical re-enactor of the French & Indian War; 
Compagnie franche de Muy, de la Marine, du Detroit.  Member of the
MidWest Tool Collector\'s Association, and Neandertal WoodDorker. 
Just Say(tm from another list), all my saws and planes are Y1K compliant.


Traveller background:  Did my graduate work at Illinois State University
in mid-late 1970\'s, when GDW was upstairs, over the Just-Rite ice-cream
shop.  I didn\'t participate in any play-testing, as pleasing Prof\'s
Mockford, Weber, and Liberta was really important, but I still have
intact copies of Raphia and of Triplanetary. %^)

Played and refereed Traveller, and some En Garde, with the CSGCI from
1980, \'til about 1990.  A gaming buddy tripped across my office, a few
months ago, and hooked me into the list.

I don\'t have the time (see other hobbies, above) to game face-to-face,
but would like to get into a PBEM game, emphasizing CT.  I always liked
Traveller, \'cause the object of the game was _to have an adventure_, not
gain points, or total up body counts.  Ask Ken Roney about one Munchkin
[aka The Incorrigible Bulk] who insisted on wearing (legal) CmbtAr while
passenger inboard a free trader - the AntiHijack kept locking him in his
stateroom, and it always took most of the ship\'s day to calm things
down. ;^>  

Steve Noe, in Indianapolis
