    'topic' => 'War of 1812 (now w/ ObTrav!)',
    'body' => 'From what I\'ve seen in documentaries and so on, the war of 1812 in North
America was a half-hearted battle between two forces that weren\'t really
all that interested.  The British had to pull some of their forces out to
fight Napoleon, some Americans saw the chance to grab some under-defended
English territory, there were some nasty skirmishes and then the British
came back and retaliated.  The initial American thrust was never really
pushed through or they could have done a lot more damage.  Once again it
was a lack of political will that was the determinant.  Likewise, the
British counter-attack wasn\'t exactly carried through to the fullest or
they could have really hurt the states.  

The part I can\'t understand was that with the British closing on
Washington, the minister of war just kept saying to the president of the
time that "they\'ll never go for the Capital".  He had no reason for this
assertion, and the president didn\'t push him on it.  When the British got
there, no one tried to stop them.  IIRC, they went up to another American
city, there met some serious resistance, and therefore decided to call it
off. (All from memory, feel free to correct)

Having said that, I think the Canadian/British side clearly won, having
sacked the capital and all.  I just don\'t see it as a particularly
glorious moment in our military history (assuming there can be glory in
war at all), as we were basically allowed to walk in.  Mind you, folks in
Halifax see it differently.  They seem quite proud that the local
university was founded with money looted from the US in that war, and that
the local government house is the longest standing leader\'s residence in
NA because "the White House would have been, but we burned it down in
1812." (nearly direct quote from Halifax tourist web-site). Silliness,
IMHO.

Okay, enough of this OT stuff.  Here\'s an ObTrav:  Are there any small
border states of the Imperium that have a similar history with them?  Is
there a moderately long-lasting Vargr band that once sacked Regina long
ago and still hails itself as the only ones to "successfully invade the
Marches"?  Or better yet, in the early history of the Imperium, did anyone
take what is now Capital, and holds that as a proud moment in their
military history?  

Charles C. (aka Chuck the Canuck)
