    'index' => 'eh841',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'Rupert Boleyn writes:
>On 19 Dec 99, at 12:44, Leonard Erickson wrote:
>>You aren\'t thinking on the right timescale. Recessive *do* get lost
>>from populations, unless they provide an advantage of some sort. But
>>it\'s a *slow* process.
>On that sort of timescale non-advantageous dominants would go, too. In 
>fact they should go faster, because they don\'t "hide" from the 
>selection process.

	Unless selection is acting on the gene, recessives are no more
	likely to be lost than dominants.  Either sort of gene might
	be lost by "genetic drift," but as Leonard pointed out it is
	a slow process.  It is also possible for a gene to "drift" to
	"fixation," that is, to become more and more common until it
	has completely taken over the population.  As Rupert mentioned,
	once selection enters the picture, recessive genes tend to
	respond more slowly, taking more time to either disappear or
	take over (depending on which way selection is acting).

Peez
