    'month' => '12',
    'topic' => ' Marooned (MegaT)',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> But seriously, we are talking survival. IMHO if you crash land in a
> polar region , I would rather expect that cold would the the most
> pressing of your worries with shelter a close second.

Shelter is generally easy. At least for a temporary shelter that\'ll cut
the wind and help you retain a lot of body heat. Build a snow cave.
Later, work on an igloo if you\'ve got the right sort of snow handy.

What would be *really* bad is landing in one of Antarctica\'s "dry
valleys". There\'s nothing but bare ground. And fairly hard packed since
over the centuries, wind has blown away anything loose. So it\'s basicly
bare rock and hardpan. Building a shelter is going to be tough. So is
finding water since it hasn\'t rained or snowed in these areas for
hundreds or *thousands* of years. Polar desert... *not* a fun terrain
type. 


> Carnivorous beasties rank third or fourth with food and water.

Water is fairly simple, again outside of those %%^^$# valleys. You just
melt snow.But be careful *how* you melt it. 

Food is the real problem. There\'s damn little living up there in the
winter. And if you aren\'t near the ocean, make that *nothing*. 

> BTW, Polar bears are notorious for hunting anything that moves on the
> ice, including man, almost always from ambush.

At least they aren\'t a problem in Antartica. :-)

