    'body' => '> >
> >Remember the War of 1812? The USA _lost_. It will
> >again!
>
>True we didn\'t suceed at the land grab. And we lost all
>of the battles except the last one (the battle of New
>Orleans - fought 2 weeks after the peace treaty was
>signed.) But we got two very important concessions
>from the Brits: 1) The british agreed to stop press ganging
>american sailors into the royal navy, and 2) The British
>stopped supporting the Indian tribes to the west of the
>US ( a significant concession in terms of US expansion.)
Sorry, guys; I have been replying off-list so far, but this is too much.
Yes, the initial thrust into Canada by militia and jumped-up colonels who 
were shopkeepers the day before were pushed back. HOWEVER, America also 
captured and destroyed the British base in York (Canada, not England), 
captured Ft. George, and won the lake battles on Erie (making Erie, in many 
ways, an \'American\' lake for many years) and Champlain. Also, *regular* 
American forces drove General Proctor into Canada, where they pursued his 
forces, caught them, and destroyed them. And, unlike an earlier post, the 
British were stopped at Ft. Meig, Ft. Stephenson, Sackett\'s Harbor and 
Baltimore (where my great-etc. grandfather was a captain in the regular 
army). So the statements that \'America only won a single battle\' and \'the 
British army marauded up and down the East Coast unopposed\' are simply 
wrong. There was a great deal of traded land, bad decisions, and weird 
coincidences on all sides.
And, again unlike an earlier post, the American navy did not have a limited 
impact. The new American frigates inflicted so much damage that the British 
navy was under orders to flee unless the American ships were outnumbered. 
there were three occasions when American ships destroyed three british ships 
in one day and a single American ship captured 10 British ships in one 
month. That\'s pretty impressive.
So, while the U.S. lost Buffalo, Detroit and Niagara, they also captured a 
fair amount of territory around Erie; more importantly, they proved that 
American regulars could meet and beat the British regulars and that American 
ships and crews could beat British ships and crews. While the U.S. had 
suffered some early losses and embarrassing defeats, they certainly had the 
initiative, especially at sea. This may explain why the British were willing 
to return their strategic gains - if they were winning, why do that?
