    'body' => 'Anthony Jackson wrote:

>There\'s no shortage of people who think a fully-reusable lifter
> wouldn\'t be very useful, the problem is that the number of
> working prototypes is currently zero, and based on the history
> of the industry, the odds of any one of various reusable
> booster schemes currently being proposed actually working as
> advertised is quite low.  Spending several years and hundreds
> of millions of dollars on something which has maybe a 20%
> chance of working is not the sort of thing that excites
> corporate sponsors....

Wilbur and Orville had similar problems a century ago. Even
supposing you did invent a machine that could fly, what use would
it possibly be? The number of working prototypes was zero, the
history of the industry was even more dismal than the aerospace
industry is now, and ISTR they got the same kind of reactions
from backers they approached.  

> Actually, expendables are cheaper than existing reusables.

What existing reusables? The four shuttle orbiters? The main fuel
tank is still a multimillion dollar throwaway, the boosters have
to be recovered from somewhere downrange and rebuilt, and the
engines have to be stripped and rebuilt after every flight. It\'s
little wonder current expendables are cheaper.  Then, too, nearly
the whole US space program and not just a comsat is riding on
each flight, so this kludge has to be made as safe to fly as
human effort can make it. By the time you count that expense in,
cheaper expendables are no wonder at all.

>Actually, the problem is that they can\'t guarantee a profit
>_ever_, and certainly aren\'t going to generate a profit in the
>next five years.

Guaranteeing any profit, let alone a quick one, is more than they
ought to do, and both companies and investors should know it.
Pioneering new technology is inherently risky. Investors
overestimating the risks and underestimating the potential return
appears to be the real problem.
 
