    'topic' => ' [OT] War of 1812',
    'body' => 'Who won, everybody\'s debating. Well, by Clausewitz\'s
definition of victory as "making the enemy do your
will," a sensible government will have a set of goals,
presumably some more important than others. Since the
USA invaded Canada, Canada\'s goal was simple: survive
as a nation. That is a greater victory than avoiding
having your citizens press-ganged into someone else\'s
navy, isn\'t it? So both sides achieved their
objectives, both sides won; but Canada\'s victory was
the greater, since it was a more important issue,
surely.

A similar example is Vietnam; the North\'s goal was to
unite Vietnam under a communist government, the USA\'s
goal was to keep the south non-communist. In that
sense, the commies won... but twenty years later
Vietnam turned around and wanted trade with the
western world, blocked by the USA, and was forced to
introduce market reforms... so now the USA has won.

I\'ll leave the ObTravs to those more knowledgeable
about Trav history! I\'m usre not all victories there
