    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>  This problem is endemic in the space industry; the shuttle was 
> _supposed_ to be exactly what you describe, it just turned out that the 
> technology of the time was not up to the task of building a fully reusable 
> SSTO.

It *was* up to it. It\'s just that Congress declined to fund it *and*
forced NASA to build a much bigger orbiter than they wanted to. The
huge size is because they has to commit to being able to boost things
like the KH series satellites to keep the funding. Then the military
turned around and dropped their interest in using the shuttle for most
missions anyway. 

If it hadn\'t been for the military satellite launch requirements, the
Shuttle cargo by would be anywhere from 2/3rd to 1/2 the size it
currently is, and the rest of the shuttle would be smaller too. 

> My basic argument here is that you seem to believe that cheap space
> travel is easy, with just a little bit of research, and that if
> corporations/nasa/ whatever would just recognize this, the problem
> would be solved. 

No, we claim that it\'s nowhere near as hard as NASA makes it look. And
that designing more robust launchers will lower costs *drastricly* even
if they have lower payload fractions. What makes Shuttle flights so
expensive *isn\'t* the cost of the fuel! And it isn\'t even the cost of
the vehicle or the parts that need replacing after every flight. It\'s
the salaries of the *huge* number of people involved in the process.

> I claim that cheap space travel is a fundamentally hard problem,
> which will require application of large amounts of time, money, and
> research.

Which is what was said about space flight *in general* years back. 

True, neither is *easy*. But they aren\'t *nearly* as hard as people
think.


> In addition, while I am not awed by NASAs performance, I haven\'t
> exactly been impressed by most of its competition either.

Keep in mind that many design that deserved to at least get tested has
been shot down when would be investors asked NASA about it. Naturally
they were told the idea was worthless. This isn\'t even necessarily
deliberate bias, just the *natural* tendency to think "if it was a good
idea, we\'d be using it".

