    'index' => 'eh940',
    'topic' => ' War of 1812 ',
    'body' => '>And, again unlike an earlier post, the American navy did not have a limited
>impact. The new American frigates inflicted so much damage that the British
>navy was under orders to flee unless the American ships were outnumbered.
>there were three occasions when American ships destroyed three british ships
>in one day and a single American ship captured 10 British ships in one
>month. That\'s pretty impressive.

The British could *afford* to only fight at odds of three to one. (And I\'d
like to
see a source for that claim, by the way. When HMS Shannon engaged and
destroyed USS Chesapeake it certainly didn\'t have any friends along...in fact,
it deliberately sent off all other ships in the squadron so it could engage
the
equivalently-sized Chesapeake one-on-one.

(For those Americans who don\'t recall the historical details, Shannon wom-
America didn\'t win *every* engagement...) (I\'ve just finished re-reading
Patrick O\'Brian\'s marvellous "The Fortune of War", which includes very
historical retellings of USS Constitution taking HMS Java and HMS Shannon
beating USS Chesapeake.)

In any event, the frigate actions - though psychologically impressive - were
nearly irrelevant strategically. British merchant shipping was
inconvienienced;
US merchant shipping was completely shut down at every port on the US.
The Royal Navy still had effectively complete sea control. The British could
land troops anywhere they wanted and there wasn\'t a damn thing the US Navy
could do about it, which is what sea control is really about.

A good analogy is WWII and the Bismark - the wonderfully advanced, very
impressive US frigates could indeed beat any single opponent, but were just
too few and far between to influence the war other than psychologically.
Not completely off topic, as "commerce raider in individually superior
cruiser"
is a good roll for Traveller PCs to play in a war...

>they certainly had the initiative, especially at sea.
>This may explain why the British were willing
>to return their strategic gains - if they were winning, why do that?
"Initiative" is a complicated thing to define. Who took the initiative in
actually
landing troops? And, in the end, landing troops and protecting merchant
shipping
is what naval power is really about.

Britain had agreed to US terms before the war even started, and had no hope
of actually holding retaken colonies, so it\'s not surprisng Britain agreed to
end the
war...Definitely a draw.

Bruce
