Ahh, the great "Who won the War of 1812" debate (seems to come up about
once a year).

> And, again unlike an earlier post, the American navy did not have a limited 
> impact. The new American frigates inflicted so much damage that the British 
> navy was under orders to flee unless the American ships were outnumbered. 
> there were three occasions when American ships destroyed three british ships 
> in one day and a single American ship captured 10 British ships in one 
> month. That\'s pretty impressive.

Well, yes and no. The naval portion of the War of 1812 is a text book case
of a minor navy (the US) following a guerre de corse against a major naval
power (the UK). The UK had world wide committents and consequently
forced to protect those interests in the most cost effective manner. Hence
the standard RN frigate as a 32 or 36 gun 5th rate. The US had no such
committments to protect and could therefore build ships that were
individually superior to the RNs, hence the USNs monster 50 gun 4th rates.
It really is no suprise that these ships defeated their RN counterparts.
However, despite their sucesses the US frigates really could do no more
than inflict a string of embarrassing pin pricks on the UKs overall maritime
position. There simply were not enough US frigates to do any real damage.
The British on the otherhand, had more than sufficent resources to totally
shut down US trade with a blockade, it may not have been spectacular
but it was certainly effective. Also once the RN commissioned their own
50 gunners, the US frigates were forced to act far more cautiously (as an
aside, the RNs 50 gunners were not built in response to the US frigates
as is often claimed, their drafts date from 1810).

ObTrav: The lessons of the War of 1812 are perfectly valid in Traveller and
very illuminating.


