    'body' => '>Actually, as Bruce has pointed out, the United States had resolved it\'s
>issues before the war began.
>
No. The US negotiated terms with the brittish AFTER the war began, but well
before it\'s end. One of the concessions was that HM RN would cease
impressing persons from US vessels. Pressing from ships underway was NOT
common; pressing sailors in port was common. Prior to the War of 1812, His
Majesty\'s Government did not recognize American Independance De Jure; that
they had accepted it De Facto didn\'t mean normalized relations. BTW, the
war was 4 years from first battle to last; 1812 was in the middle.

>The real reason for the US launching the war was that they thought the
>Canadian colonies would be an easy mark with Britain busy on the continent.

A goal that had been abortively attempted prior; not mentioned at all in
the declaration of war. The US goal, if any were set, was recognition AS A
GOVERNMENT; cessation of pressing US sailors AT SEA was recognition that
they were under the flag of a nation, not a brittish colony. Brittain had
been defending their actions by claiming that the US was, in fact, not a
state, but 13 rebellious colonies.

>What makes you think it didn\'t demonstrate "Staying power"

Item: The Brittish formally recognized the US.
Item: The brittish raided, but did not attempt to take, US Cities.
Item: The Brittish did not mobilize their army in any great force.
Item: The proof that HMRN was, in fact, not the be-all and end-all of seapower

>>and in not losing Canada.
>
>>Instead of calling it a draw one might accurately state that both
>> sides were victorious in that they got what they wanted.
>
Quite literally, it was a PR coup for the US; while merchant shipping to
and from the US may have been slowed to a trickle (some blockade running
did occur), it did not prevent the US from projecting force on the seas,
all the way to Tripoli. This last is memorialized by the new branch of the
US military which was raised due to the war in their hymn: "From the Halls
of Montezuma,/ to the Shores of Tripoli / We will fight our country\'s
battles / On the land as on the sea." Yes, Uncle Sam\'s Musket and Cutlas,
Uncle Sam\'s Misguided Children, the US Marine Corps. The war also served to
unify the colonies at a time where framentation seemed immanent. If nothing
else, the internal changes brought about by the War of 1812 were as
important as the recognition by HMG.

That the US forces fought as well as they did started a breakdown of the
Status Quo in Europe, as well.

Fundamentally a war is fought for some form of gain. For brittain, there
was not enough force to be brought to bear IN TIME, at LOW ENOUGH COST, for
them to conttinue the fighting. For the US, until they could establish that
they were, in fact, not just a rebelious colony, but a nation-state of
their own, they were not taken seriously (France being notable in the
exception, but france had other reasons, specifically, keeping Brittain off
their own back, for encouraging the US vs UK interactions). By getting the
concessions from brittain (by far a cheaper solution than retaking the 13
colonies or indefinite blockade, especially since cotton and tobacco were
major Brittish imports), the US enforced enough political will to gain
recognition.

Ob Trav: The Frontier Wars are, quite obviously, NOT about territorial
needs for the Zhodani; The 3I doesn\'t really NEED expansion room for the
first one. On the interstellar scale, basics of resources don\'t make for
enough of a prize to justify the war. Next comes Politcal Will and
Ideology; here we find a fit to the canon. The only reason for the war
would be to establish and maintain a firm border, so as to prevent
"Imperialization" of the border areas.

Likewise, the Interstellar wars, in the days of the Vilani Imperium, are
not so much about resources as "Manifest Destiny". The VI seems to have a
desire to rull all of mankind. The Terran Confed cannot threaten the VI as
a whole. At least, they could not do so in any meaningful military way
during any single war. The whole issue is one of gaining enough to
consolidate, and gain some more after the consolidation. The Plague of
Duskir changed the ballance immensely; The TC, which had NO CHANCE of
peaceful long-term co-existance, was able to defeat the decimated VI Navy.
From the perspective of the VI, the "Upstarts" were just a threat, one that
kepttaking more and more, and needed to be stopped, and then, as was their
standing manifest destiny, erradicated as an interstellar-nation-state,
integrated, and culturally subsumed.

Hmmm... I think I see a pattern here...


