    'body' => 'Rick Stump writes:

>Sorry, guys; I have been replying off-list so far, but this is too much.
>[...]
>And, again unlike an earlier post, the American navy did not have a limited 
>impact. The new American frigates inflicted so much damage that the British 
>navy was under orders to flee unless the American ships were outnumbered. 

I too have kept quiet because this really has no place on the TML, but the
subject is one that interests me and I just can\'t let this go.

Actually, one of the reasons why the American frigates were so succesful was
that British frigate captains couldn\'t flee from them. The Admiralty expected
any British ship to be able to outfight anything in its own class. A frigate
could flee from a ship-of-the-line, but if it fled from another frigate the
captain risked being hung for cowardice. At the very least he could expect
to be beached. It made no difference that the \'frigate\' was larger and had
scantlings like a ship-of-the-line. It may be that Admiralty orders eventually
allowed small British frigates to avoid action against American 44s, although
I have not heard of that. Do you have a source for this allegation?

In any case, the British eventually got their act together and proceeded to
sweep the seas clear of American shipping. I refer you to C.S. Forester\'s
_The Age of Fighting Sail_ for a thorough exploration of the seaborne side
of the war.

>there were three occasions when American ships destroyed three british ships 
>in one day and a single American ship captured 10 British ships in one 
>month. That\'s pretty impressive.

Unless you\'re talking about American privateers capturing British merchantmen,
then you are misinformed. The American Navy didn\'t capture or destroy 19
British naval vessels in the whole war. I doubt they even _fought_ 19 naval
engagements in the whole war.

>While the U.S. had suffered some early losses and embarrassing defeats, they
>certainly had the initiative, especially at sea. 

That just isn\'t true. At the time peace was signed very few American Navy
ships were at liberty. Most had been captured, destroyed (some of them by 
their own crew to prevent the British from capturing them) or blockaded.
I\'m not sure a single frigate was at liberty, though I may be wrong about
that; a few sloops is all, IIRC.

>This may explain why the British were willing to return their strategic 
>gains - if they were winning, why do that?

The British public was tired after two decades of war, income tax was 4
shillings in the pound, and Wellington had expressed doubts that America
could ever be completely defeated in a land war (certainly not without an
effort similar in scope to the one that had defeated Napoleon), and the RN
no longer felt the need to impress American sailors or blockade European
ports.

If America won the War of 1812 then it was by default; the other side quit
and went home...


